WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.840
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:35.280
[Amit Varma]: Indian women are an unseen nation and for those of you who like counterfactual history,

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:40.240
[Amit Varma]: here's a question I'd like to ask. What would India have looked like if our women were as

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:45.200
[Amit Varma]: empowered as men? There are figures that attempt an economic answer to that question.

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:49.680
[Amit Varma]: The journalist Namita Bhandare, my guest on the show today, once pointed out that if women

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:57.600
[Amit Varma]: participated in the economy at par with men, our GDP would go up by 60% or $2.9 trillion by 2025.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:04.160
[Amit Varma]: Our Prime Minister talks about a $5 trillion economy. Easy game. But even economic estimates

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:08.880
[Amit Varma]: cover up the real problem. The truth is that women are second class citizens in India,

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:13.360
[Amit Varma]: treated practically as a separate species. They are confined to strict gender roles,

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:18.320
[Amit Varma]: often confined in their homes, treated as a property of men, rather than as autonomous

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:22.800
[Amit Varma]: human beings. Even when they are in the workplace, they are treated as lesser beings,

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:28.080
[Amit Varma]: trained not to speak up at meetings, trained to be subservient, with exceptions that stand

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:32.640
[Amit Varma]: out as exceptions and thus tend to prove the rule. You could say that the women of India

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:38.560
[Amit Varma]: are an invisible country colonized by the visible country of men. Just imagine if this nation of

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:45.120
[Amit Varma]: more than 600 million people could reach its full economic and social and creative and political

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:54.720
[Unknown]: potential. Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and

00:01:54.720 --> 00:02:01.520
[Amit Varma]: behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma. Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:02:01.520 --> 00:02:06.000
[Amit Varma]: My guest on the show today is a journalist, Namita Bhandare, whose journalism I've been a

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.400
[Amit Varma]: fan of for many years, and I'm so glad I finally got her on the show. The subject we are going to

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:15.520
[Amit Varma]: explore today is women at work, a subject on which she wrote a brilliant nine part series

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:20.000
[Amit Varma]: on India spend a couple of years ago, which will be linked from the show notes. She's written

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.680
[Amit Varma]: perceptively on Indian society and not just women's issues for literally decades now. And

00:02:25.680 --> 00:02:42.960
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to make you wait around 60 seconds more as we go into a quick commercial break.

00:02:56.400 --> 00:03:00.880
[Amit Varma]: As long as the sponsor the show, I'm going to recommend one book a week that I love. The book

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:06.400
[Amit Varma]: I want to recommend today is after the piece by the brilliant novelist Faye Weldon, which begins

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:11.840
[Amit Varma]: with the intriguing question, how many parents does it take to make a baby? The answer it seems

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:17.920
[Amit Varma]: is four. For more, check it out on Storytel. And remember, you get a 30 day free trial,

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:24.880
[Amit Varma]: only at Storytel.com slash IVM. Namita, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:26.800
[Guest]: Hi, Amit. Thanks for having me here.

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:32.400
[Amit Varma]: Namita, before we get to the rather depressing subject at hand,

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:36.640
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit more about yourself. How did you get into journalism and so on?

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:42.880
[Guest]: Okay, just a small correction before we start talking about myself. It's not depressing. The

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:49.280
[Guest]: women of India, to me represent a great hope and a great aspiration. We will talk about that in

00:03:49.280 --> 00:04:01.120
[Guest]: detail. I will tell you a little bit about myself. I'm a mother of two women, 26 and 24. I have been

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:06.720
[Guest]: a journalist for nearly 30 years, starting my career in a lot of publications that have since

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:13.440
[Guest]: folded up, including the Indian Post, Sunday Magazine, where I had some of my best experiences

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:22.960
[Guest]: of long form writing, and finally, ending with Hindustan Times. I was also Mint's first gender

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:29.680
[Guest]: editor. I believe the country's first gender editor ever. Sukumar took a great risk with me,

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:36.080
[Guest]: and I will always be grateful for that big break. We had a lot of fun exploring gender,

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:41.760
[Guest]: not as a little silo. We did talk about, I remember when we first talked about how we

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:51.120
[Guest]: should be covering gender, we wondered whether we should have a weekly gender page and then decided

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:59.120
[Guest]: that that was just too retro, because gender does not exist in a silo. We are 50% of the population

00:04:59.120 --> 00:05:04.400
[Guest]: and gender is everywhere. It means looking at your op-ed pages, do you have enough women's

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:09.760
[Guest]: voices coming in? It means looking at your hardcore business pages, are you quoting enough

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:18.160
[Guest]: women? And it was interesting because we actually thought about bringing in a gender editor much

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:24.560
[Guest]: before the New York Times did. The New York Times now has an entire gender team. I've met with some

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:30.080
[Guest]: of them, they're fantastic women, but we were first. That's amazing. And you know, I started

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:36.480
[Amit Varma]: my career in the 90s, but you started in the late 80s. And I remember back then it almost felt like

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:41.200
[Amit Varma]: women are sort of stereotyped in journalism and the kind of roles they occupy. Like if,

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:46.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, women were supposed to do the soft stuff, the features and so on and the hard news and

00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:52.800
[Amit Varma]: the reporting wasn't something women really did. Is that kind of true? And did you face any

00:05:52.800 --> 00:05:58.000
[Guest]: barriers back then and the kind of work you wanted to do? You know, Amit, forget about media.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:06.400
[Guest]: With every generation of women, there has been an entirely new set of struggles. So the generation

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:14.400
[Guest]: before me, and I'm talking about the great women journalists like Usha Rai or Barkha's mom,

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:18.320
[Guest]: you know, so, you know, these were women who were opening the doors, Kumi Kapoor,

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:22.400
[Guest]: they were opening the doors. You never saw women in the newsroom. There were no separate

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:28.560
[Guest]: toilets for women because women were not supposed to be in the newsroom. So that was a different

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:34.080
[Guest]: battle. They opened the doors for us. We stood on their shoulders. When I came in, yes, you're

00:06:34.080 --> 00:06:39.520
[Guest]: right. There was the stereotyping. Women were supposed to still do the soft stories. You were

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:45.600
[Guest]: on the art beat. You were on the profile beat. The magazine sections were filled with women.

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:51.520
[Guest]: And that has changed. That has changed. Today, when you walk into a newsroom, you will be struck

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:58.560
[Guest]: by the number of women you see on the floor. And yet, some things persist. So you see the women

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:04.080
[Guest]: in the news floor in abundance. But the people in the corner rooms, in the corner offices are all

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:10.880
[Guest]: men. So that still has to be very few women. Television has been great and has been far more

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:16.400
[Guest]: and has been far more progressive than print in that sense where you have a lot of women who are

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:22.800
[Guest]: in charge. NDTV is a sterling example where women have been in charge from day one. Print has been

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:28.320
[Guest]: a bit slow to catch up. So you see a lot of women in the newsroom, not so many women in leadership

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:33.280
[Amit Varma]: positions. What was your early journalism like? Like, how did it evolve? How did your interest

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:38.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of evolve in the directions it did in? And at some point you chose to give it up and go

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:44.560
[Guest]: freelance. So tell me a bit about that. Yes. So I had done my master's in journalism from

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:52.160
[Guest]: Stanford. I came back and frankly, the master's at Stanford was a fig leaf. You know, I was lucky

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:57.680
[Guest]: to get a fellowship. And so I could run away. But it was a fig leaf because I knew that if I

00:07:57.680 --> 00:08:04.320
[Guest]: stayed on in India, I would marry a bhala ladka from a bhala family and fulfill my mother's

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:09.520
[Guest]: wildest dreams. And so I said, I mean, I had other plans. So, you know, it was just,

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:15.520
[Guest]: you know, we forget now because we see so many women. I mean, women studying is not a big deal.

00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:21.760
[Guest]: But when I went in 86, 87 to the US to study, there were hardly any women who are going abroad.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:28.560
[Guest]: You know, it was a big deal. But because I had a fellowship, my mother could not exactly object.

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:33.840
[Guest]: You know, I was saying, I don't need your money. I'm going. Which Indian will say no to freebies?

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:41.200
[Guest]: Well, this was yes, exactly. So my mother was not happy, but she understood. And then of course,

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:47.280
[Guest]: when I came back, I said, I want to come back to Bombay. I started working in the Indian Post

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:54.480
[Guest]: and it was exhilarating, you know, to be living alone in Bombay at that time. I'm talking about

00:08:54.480 --> 00:09:02.160
[Guest]: 89, 90. The Indian Post was a very young paper full of just brilliant people. You know, Alan

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:08.080
[Guest]: Twig, the late film critic, he was a friend of mine. I mean, there was just an energy and a buzz

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:14.960
[Guest]: that Vinod Mehta brought with him to the paper. It's an old story. The Indian Post folded up,

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:20.560
[Guest]: actually. Vinod went on to forming a new paper. I did not go at that time. I was

00:09:20.560 --> 00:09:26.080
[Guest]: young, idealistic, and foolish. And I believed I will stay on. So we were about 15 of us,

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:32.000
[Guest]: helped by the Bombay Union of Journalists, taking out this paper somehow or the other every year,

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:38.560
[Guest]: every day, I'm sorry. And then it was eventually bought by Gujarat Samachar. And it was basically,

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:41.920
[Guest]: it was, you know, we had seen the writing on the wall, it was time to move on.

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:49.600
[Guest]: I then ended up working for a while with Sunday Magazine, as I mentioned, some of my best years.

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:55.520
[Guest]: I learned a lot. Veer Sanghvi was the great editor and a great teacher, and very trusting

00:09:55.520 --> 00:10:02.560
[Guest]: in allowing young people, inexperienced people to go out and do stories. And in his mind,

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:08.080
[Guest]: there was no, you know, gender bias in the sense that the hard political stories were being done

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:14.240
[Guest]: by men. In fact, our great political editor who continues to write a column for Business Standard

00:10:14.240 --> 00:10:20.640
[Guest]: was Aditi Fadnis, a wonderful teacher, a wonderful mentor, and a wonderful role model. And so we had

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:26.400
[Guest]: women in charge of the hard stuff, the nuts and bolts. So there was nothing that we could not do,

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:30.320
[Guest]: whether it was foreign policy, whether it was politics, whether it was back of the book,

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:36.240
[Guest]: the soft, so-called women's stuff. We did it all. We were everywhere. It was a small team,

00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:41.840
[Guest]: you were expected to do it all. And then Sunday, kind of, as Sunday was folding up,

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:48.400
[Guest]: I moved to India today. I worked there for a couple of years. I then eventually went back

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:55.200
[Guest]: to working with Veer in the Hindustan Times. I remember 9-11 had just happened and he reached

00:10:55.200 --> 00:11:00.640
[Guest]: out to me. He said, why don't you come back and work in Hindustan Times? We'll work together.

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:08.880
[Guest]: Once again, very trusting in terms of the kind of leeway and the kind of responsibilities he was

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:19.120
[Guest]: giving. By this time, I was already a mother of two young girls. And so my condition with Veer was,

00:11:19.120 --> 00:11:24.400
[Guest]: I'll come back, but I will work part-time. So I need to be out of here at five o'clock.

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:33.520
[Guest]: And he understood that. And so my pay was also part-time. And then I realized very quickly

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:40.880
[Guest]: that part-time was a convenient designation to pay me half of what everybody else was being paid.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:47.520
[Guest]: But my output was actually full-time because I was producing a page a day, I was writing stories,

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:53.200
[Guest]: I was editing stuff. We had a youth page, a weekly youth page, which I was in charge of.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.880
[Guest]: And of course, it was all the undercurrent that you got from your male colleagues. Because at

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:05.520
[Guest]: five o'clock when I was picking up my bag to head home, there were guys who were saying,

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:10.400
[Guest]: oh, how nice of you to drop in, Mrs. Bhandare. They would call me, how nice of you to drop in,

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:16.080
[Guest]: Mrs. Bhandare, have a good time. And I was like, bloody hell, you just got in half an hour ago

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:20.640
[Guest]: because you were at the press club and you were having a big boozy lunch and then downing a

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:25.920
[Guest]: couple of black coffees to get over the big boozy lunch and you're getting down to work now.

00:12:25.920 --> 00:12:32.160
[Guest]: I've finished my work because I've been here since 10 o'clock. So it was an interesting insight. Of

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:36.720
[Guest]: course, at that time, I didn't know I'd be doing the Women and Work series, but I was kind of,

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:43.680
[Guest]: I was my first example of just how impossible it was to balance this work-life balance.

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:50.800
[Guest]: And so I went full-time. I told Veer, I said, my output is that of a full-time person.

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:56.720
[Guest]: I want my salary. And I think women don't do this enough. We don't ask for the money that we think

00:12:56.720 --> 00:13:01.520
[Guest]: we're worth. And so I told him, I said, I think you should pay me a full-time salary and I will

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:06.480
[Guest]: work full-time. And so I started working full-time, which meant, because I was editing the Saturday

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:12.160
[Guest]: paper at the time, I would never get home before midnight on Friday night because I had to put the

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:17.680
[Guest]: paper to bed. And because I wanted to get a headstart on Friday, I would be working late

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:25.840
[Guest]: till Thursday, which was like 10 o'clock. And so what was happening in a predominantly male,

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:31.600
[Guest]: the heads of department were all men. So whether it was the designer, whether it was the photographer,

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:36.080
[Guest]: whether it was the desk guys, they were men. So even if you came in at nine o'clock,

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:42.000
[Guest]: the other guys were not coming in till 11 o'clock, 12 o'clock. Then you'd have these

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:48.000
[Guest]: long edit meetings. Then everybody would run off to press club. So your workflow began

00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:54.400
[Guest]: only at five o'clock. And if you're heading a department, you realize that you can't work alone.

00:13:54.400 --> 00:14:02.000
[Guest]: You need your team with you. And here is a generational change. So I tried it for a while,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:07.600
[Guest]: and then it was just untenable. My children by then were adolescents. I had a Eureka moment,

00:14:07.600 --> 00:14:13.920
[Guest]: actually, literally in the shower where I said, if I drop dead, my family is not even going to

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:20.480
[Guest]: get a discount on the obituary, let alone a free subscription to HD for even the next six months.

00:14:20.480 --> 00:14:25.600
[Guest]: But for my children, I'm indispensable. And it was just something had to give. And so I decided

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:31.680
[Guest]: to chuck up full-time working. And I went into writing a column and I went into freelance work.

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:38.160
[Guest]: It's a struggle, but I've never looked back. I've never regretted that decision. But coming back to

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:46.080
[Guest]: the generational change, 10 years later, when my friend Priya Ramani took over as the editor of

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:53.920
[Guest]: Mint Lounge, she had basically an all women team. And so she could lay down the law. And that was

00:14:53.920 --> 00:14:59.280
[Guest]: the difference. I could not lay down the law because I was dependent on all these male colleagues

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:04.080
[Guest]: who simply could not understand why they needed to come early and leave early. So she laid down

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:08.720
[Guest]: the law. She said, everybody in at 10 o'clock, and it's pens down at five o'clock, go home.

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:12.080
[Guest]: And even if you're not married, it doesn't matter. Even if you don't have children,

00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:17.280
[Guest]: it doesn't matter. Go home, watch a movie, read a book, because there is life outside the office.

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:23.120
[Guest]: And so that's what she changed the work environment, at least in her department.

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:28.240
[Amit Varma]: I was unable to do that. Good for Priya. And you've written a really nice piece about,

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:32.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, going freelance and all of this in a site called SheRoes. So that's a lovely piece,

00:15:32.960 --> 00:15:40.240
[Amit Varma]: and I'll link that from the show notes. How has, you know, two sort of questions. One is that

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:43.920
[Amit Varma]: when you did your course in journalism in Stanford, there must have been certain

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:48.160
[Amit Varma]: expectations you had of what journalism should be, what are the best practices and so on.

00:15:48.800 --> 00:15:52.400
[Amit Varma]: So question number one, how was the reality different when you got down to India? Though,

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:56.240
[Amit Varma]: of course, you did work with good editors in terms of Vinod Mehta and Veer Sanghvi,

00:15:56.240 --> 00:16:01.760
[Amit Varma]: but how was the reality different? And looking at journalism in India today is 2019. And when

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:07.440
[Amit Varma]: you compare it to, you know, 30 years ago, when you started, what are the big changes that you've

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:15.120
[Guest]: seen? So at Stanford, we pretty much followed the American style of journalism, which is

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:21.520
[Guest]: objectivity is king. You know, you are objective, come what may, you are never part of the story.

00:16:21.520 --> 00:16:26.560
[Guest]: And I began my journalism pretty much like that, because that is what Vinod also believed,

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:31.440
[Guest]: and that is what Veer Sanghvi also believed. You were allowed your stylistic flourishes,

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:36.240
[Guest]: but you were supposed to be objective, you were supposed to be speaking to all sides of the story,

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:42.720
[Guest]: and so on and so forth. And I pretty much believed as that tenet of journalism,

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:50.240
[Guest]: as a gospel truth, I never questioned it until December 2012, which is when Jyoti Singh Pandey

00:16:50.240 --> 00:16:59.040
[Guest]: was gang raped and murdered in a bus in Delhi. And at that point, Amit, it became impossible for

00:16:59.040 --> 00:17:05.920
[Guest]: me to say I am objective. It became impossible for me to say I am not part of the story because

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:15.200
[Guest]: I was also protesting. I'm also a citizen, I'm also a mother. And that crime and that story just

00:17:15.200 --> 00:17:22.720
[Guest]: moved me in a way that I cannot adequately explain, even today. I remember the first time

00:17:22.720 --> 00:17:31.760
[Guest]: I met her mother. I was making a film for Channel News Asia in Singapore, and we were four of us

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:37.920
[Guest]: in her little house. At that time, they had a two-bedroom house. They've now moved to another

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:43.200
[Guest]: place, which the government gave them. And the mother, I'll never forget that. I mean,

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:50.800
[Guest]: it's one of those pivotal moments in journalism, which just reach deep inside you.

00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:58.800
[Guest]: So the daughter had just died maybe a month ago, and it was still winter, and she was lying in bed,

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:05.200
[Guest]: and she just looked up. She had this bright pink blanket covering her, and she looked up at me.

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:11.360
[Guest]: And we were three or four people in the room. There was a cameraman, there was a sound recordist,

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:17.280
[Guest]: there was me, there was the producer, and we just wept. For five minutes, we sat in the room,

00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:24.240
[Guest]: and we just cried and cried and cried. And that's when I realized that I can no longer be objective.

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:30.640
[Guest]: So today, my question is not, are you objective about the story? Today, my question is only,

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:38.880
[Guest]: are you fair? So I write on gender, and I feel that it is impossible to be objective about gender,

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:43.840
[Guest]: and it is also morally wrong. Why should I be objective about rape? I mean, can you be objective

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:51.200
[Guest]: about rape, or crimes against women, or patriarchy, or caste? Because you have so many intersections,

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:57.440
[Guest]: caste and gender. I feel it's impossible, and it's morally wrong. I feel it's ethically and

00:18:57.440 --> 00:19:02.240
[Guest]: morally... I'm not going to be objective about rape, and I'm not going to say, oh, am I being

00:19:02.240 --> 00:19:09.360
[Guest]: objective? I must present the rapist's point of view. No, I cannot be. But I can be fair. So if

00:19:09.360 --> 00:19:16.400
[Guest]: you look at, for instance, this much maligned section 498A, one of the stories that I did do

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:26.080
[Guest]: for Mint was looking at why this 498A section, which is the dowry section, is misused by women.

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:30.880
[Guest]: So fair, I'm balancing it out, right? I'm not saying that I'm giving up. I'm not saying dowry

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:37.520
[Guest]: death is great, or dowry is great, because I cannot take that position. And no citizen of a

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:42.400
[Guest]: modern democracy can take that position. You know, I believe in the constitution, I believe in

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:48.640
[Guest]: equality. But I can say, well, why is it being misused? Where are we going wrong? Is there

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:53.680
[Amit Varma]: something we can do to rectify it? And, you know, I think at some level,

00:19:53.680 --> 00:19:59.680
[Amit Varma]: objectivity in journalism can be overstated, because much as one should attempt to be

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:04.000
[Amit Varma]: objective and see all sides of the issue, it's also true that all human beings are fundamentally

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:08.880
[Amit Varma]: biased anyway. And just the data you choose to present in your story, the way you choose to

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:14.000
[Amit Varma]: present it kind of affects that. And I must say that having read so much of your reportage on,

00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:19.760
[Amit Varma]: for example, the state of women across the country and in Haryana, which we'll talk about later,

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:22.880
[Amit Varma]: I don't really sense anything that is not objective there. I mean, you just present

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:26.000
[Guest]: the data and let it speak for itself. Yeah, well, that's some of my, I mean,

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:32.720
[Guest]: some of my journalism, in one of my journalistic hats, I'm a columnist. So I'm expected to present

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:38.320
[Guest]: a point of view and a perspective. That is the very definition of my job. I mean, people read

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:44.000
[Guest]: the edit page because they want to know what do you think, right? And then there is the data

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:49.760
[Guest]: journalism, which I do for websites like India Spend or for even other websites, where you're

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:53.920
[Guest]: asking, okay, have I spoken to all sides of the story? Am I presenting? And you're absolutely

00:20:53.920 --> 00:20:59.680
[Guest]: right. You look at data because if you look at a bare report, how you interpret that report is

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:05.680
[Guest]: really up to you. What am I looking for in that report? So for a lot of my gender reporting,

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:09.680
[Guest]: I am looking and I'm saying, well, this is according to government because when I'm

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:14.720
[Guest]: challenged sometimes on social media, for instance, domestic violence, the figure that

00:21:14.720 --> 00:21:20.480
[Guest]: seems to shock everybody as if it's something that is happening on planet Mars is that one

00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:27.600
[Guest]: in three women have experienced or are experiencing domestic violence at the hands of a spouse.

00:21:27.600 --> 00:21:32.400
[Guest]: And they say, no, no, it cannot be. How can it be? That means one in three, if I'm sitting in a,

00:21:32.400 --> 00:21:38.160
[Guest]: let's say in a bus where there are 10 women, I mean, you know, you've got, I'm very bad with

00:21:38.160 --> 00:21:42.160
[Guest]: math. So, but you know what I mean? So you have, you know, one in three who have experienced.

00:21:44.240 --> 00:21:49.440
[Guest]: Absolutely. So the data doesn't tell you that story. And then you tell, so you say, well,

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:52.800
[Guest]: and so people say it can't be happening. And you say, well, no, it happens. This is

00:21:52.800 --> 00:21:58.640
[Guest]: national family health survey for, and this is the data on page. So, and so this, there's the link

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:02.720
[Guest]: and please go and look at it. And then they say, oh, you know, but it must be happening to

00:22:02.720 --> 00:22:09.840
[Guest]: those people. Yeah. It doesn't happen amongst us. You know, 30%, it doesn't happen amongst us. Well,

00:22:09.840 --> 00:22:13.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, where do you think it's happening then? And what I'm struck by is, you know,

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:17.840
[Amit Varma]: when all of this difficult data comes up and all these numbers come up, which indicate that,

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:21.040
[Amit Varma]: uh, you know, women are having the kind of time they're having that men get so defensive.

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:30.640
[Guest]: Of course. And there is much to be defensive about. And there's always my favorite accusation

00:22:30.640 --> 00:22:36.640
[Guest]: that comes from men is that, oh, you are women of privilege. You know, the, I was at the Brookings

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:41.680
[Guest]: Institute. We were having a very interesting discussion on gender in the Northeast with

00:22:41.680 --> 00:22:46.960
[Guest]: Patricia Mukhim, who is the editor of Shillong Times and Mani Shankar Iyer got up and he said,

00:22:46.960 --> 00:22:52.560
[Guest]: oh, y'all are all parkati, because we were talking about 33% reservation and the need to get more

00:22:52.560 --> 00:22:56.400
[Guest]: women in parliament. And he said, but y'all are all parkati aurats, you know, I mean,

00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:01.840
[Guest]: he used parkati in inverted commas, of course. And I'm like, yeah, you could be a woman of

00:23:01.840 --> 00:23:07.600
[Guest]: privilege and still be discriminated against. So maybe I am not as discriminated against

00:23:07.600 --> 00:23:12.560
[Guest]: a Dalit woman who's living in a village or a tribal woman who's in the, having her land being

00:23:12.560 --> 00:23:18.160
[Guest]: stolen or, you know, being shot by the land mafia. But I am being discriminated against.

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:24.960
[Guest]: There is no denial of that. And I think men simply do not see, they are oblivious

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:32.720
[Guest]: to the lived realities of women. They just have no idea what it is like to walk on the street and

00:23:32.720 --> 00:23:38.480
[Guest]: have everybody stare. They have no idea of what it is like to walk in the street and never make

00:23:38.480 --> 00:23:44.000
[Guest]: eye contact. That's the first rule. You learn it as a child. You do not make eye contact because

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:49.840
[Guest]: the other guy is going to either be making a lewd face at you or blowing you a kiss or scratching

00:23:49.840 --> 00:23:54.080
[Guest]: himself somewhere. So you would just walk straight. It's like you just have these blinkers.

00:23:54.080 --> 00:23:57.600
[Guest]: You're like a racehorse. You're just walking straight and you're not looking anywhere.

00:23:57.600 --> 00:24:03.200
[Guest]: You've got your arms crossed around so that nobody touches you in parts that are vulnerable.

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:08.960
[Guest]: Well, men don't get this. They don't. And so, you know, the best men will tell me,

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:13.840
[Amit Varma]: I didn't realize. I'm sorry. I didn't realize. In fact, as we were, you know, chatting about

00:24:13.840 --> 00:24:18.240
[Amit Varma]: before we met, I mean, that's one of the realizations that happened to me well into my

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:24.880
[Amit Varma]: adulthood in the last few years is that, you know, in everything I do, I don't need to, my gender is

00:24:24.880 --> 00:24:28.640
[Amit Varma]: not a factor. I could be walking in the street. I could be meeting someone new at a party. My

00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:33.280
[Amit Varma]: gender is simply not a factor. I can make eye contact with anyone I want. I can smile whenever

00:24:33.280 --> 00:24:39.280
[Amit Varma]: I want. I don't. But in every single thing women do, including Perkitty women and women of privilege,

00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:43.600
[Amit Varma]: your gender does become a factor. It's hanging over you like a shroud and you have to just be

00:24:44.240 --> 00:24:50.720
[Amit Varma]: careful all the time. And this extra layer of consideration that women have to carry about in

00:24:50.720 --> 00:24:55.920
[Amit Varma]: their everyday lives is almost heartbreaking. And I would not say that men are culpable for this,

00:24:55.920 --> 00:25:01.680
[Amit Varma]: but it is certainly incumbent upon them to kind of take this into consideration.

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:07.040
[Guest]: Absolutely. Men as well as women. But before I get to that, I just wanted to share an

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:14.480
[Guest]: interesting story, which goes back again to the December 2012 protests. So I'm walking

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:20.720
[Guest]: up Rajpath towards Rashtrapati Bhavan, which is where the crowd is moving. And I'm walking with

00:25:20.720 --> 00:25:29.040
[Guest]: a male friend of mine. We're walking together. And there is this very striking woman. I never

00:25:29.040 --> 00:25:34.640
[Guest]: saw her face. She's a tall woman walking. There's a yellow line, a thick yellow line that divides

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:41.680
[Guest]: the two sides of the road. So she's walking alone, bang on the yellow line. And I tell my friend

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:46.240
[Guest]: Javed, who I'm walking with, I said, Javed, there are four men coming on the opposite side. I can

00:25:46.240 --> 00:25:52.240
[Guest]: see the men coming on the opposite side towards this woman. And I tell my friend Javed, I said,

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:59.040
[Guest]: Javed, just wait and watch what will happen. And here we are at a protest, four women protesting

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:04.560
[Guest]: violence against women. And these are four men. They're inoffensive, harmless guys. They're having

00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:08.480
[Guest]: fun. They're slapping each other on the back. They're laughing. They're walking in the opposite

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:14.640
[Guest]: direction. Sure enough, as soon as they come close to the woman, the woman gets off the yellow line

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:21.280
[Guest]: and walks around the men. The men are not doing anything, but there is some inbuilt signal in this

00:26:21.280 --> 00:26:28.560
[Guest]: woman that tells her, get off the line because these guys won't budge. And this is what we learn

00:26:28.560 --> 00:26:34.400
[Guest]: from childhood, whether it is in a public park, whether it is traveling in the bus, sitting next

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:40.960
[Guest]: to a guy who's nicely spread out. I was on a flight very recently and this man, I'm on the

00:26:40.960 --> 00:26:45.600
[Guest]: middle seat. So the two men on each sides have taken the armrest because, you know, it belongs

00:26:45.600 --> 00:26:51.760
[Guest]: to them. So, you know, we are, this is our conditioning. We're taught from a very young age,

00:26:51.760 --> 00:26:58.400
[Guest]: public spaces belong to men. You do not belong here. No, in fact, on flights, I myself seen that

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:02.240
[Amit Varma]: even if you don't take the armrest and there's a woman next to you, she will not put her elbows

00:27:02.240 --> 00:27:07.040
[Amit Varma]: there at all. Just completely avoid the situation. While if it's men, you're basically just elbowing

00:27:07.040 --> 00:27:11.760
[Guest]: each other by the end of it because male ego, you want that space. Which woman wants to get

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:17.920
[Amit Varma]: into that elbow fight? You just sit hunched, you know, with your arms. No, I actually encourage my

00:27:18.560 --> 00:27:22.080
[Amit Varma]: listeners, both men and women to actually do this. Let's sit for a while in a public space,

00:27:22.080 --> 00:27:27.840
[Amit Varma]: like a cafe or looking out into a park and just see how people walk around and the way they behave.

00:27:27.840 --> 00:27:33.520
[Amit Varma]: And it's visible every day in front of us and yet invisible, which is kind of poignant.

00:27:33.520 --> 00:27:37.920
[Guest]: Yeah. So, when you're talking about the unseen nation, I found your introduction, by the way,

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:43.600
[Guest]: very beautiful and very poignant. And if you go, I'm not talking about going to a small city

00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:48.720
[Guest]: or a small town, I'm saying step outside in Delhi, you know, right outside here, there's a park.

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:55.280
[Guest]: I promise you, I guarantee to you, all the kids who are playing sport, you know, whether it's

00:27:55.280 --> 00:28:01.760
[Guest]: cricket or gilli danda or whatever, are boys. Where are the girls? So, if you do see girls in

00:28:01.760 --> 00:28:07.600
[Guest]: the park, you'll either see very young children who are on the swings and slides or the adolescent

00:28:07.600 --> 00:28:11.760
[Guest]: girls are just walking. You know, they just keep going for sare, you know, just walking round and

00:28:11.760 --> 00:28:17.520
[Guest]: round. It's like girls do not have a right even to play. We are recording this in house cars,

00:28:17.520 --> 00:28:23.520
[Amit Varma]: by the way, but this is probably true of pretty much every park, frankly. Let's kind of move on

00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:29.360
[Amit Varma]: to the subject of today's episode. And, you know, I'll kind of question what you said earlier a

00:28:29.360 --> 00:28:34.960
[Amit Varma]: little bit in the sense that I think a lot of the data that you've presented in your India Spent

00:28:34.960 --> 00:28:39.680
[Amit Varma]: Pieces, some of which I'll be quoting back at you, is objective. I mean, the data speaks for itself.

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:44.560
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't matter who you the writer are. The data does a whole job and there's no other way of

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:51.280
[Amit Varma]: looking at it. And, you know, much as people like I often think that in India, every crisis we talk

00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:57.520
[Amit Varma]: about has a deeper crisis embedded within it, which is a women's crisis. For example, people

00:28:57.520 --> 00:29:02.560
[Amit Varma]: talk about the crisis in agriculture, which I have written about at length as well. And within that,

00:29:02.560 --> 00:29:07.280
[Amit Varma]: there is a greater crisis because women have it far worse. And one of those crisis, which we,

00:29:07.280 --> 00:29:12.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, again, I've had episodes on the jobs crisis in the past. And within the jobs crisis,

00:29:12.320 --> 00:29:17.840
[Amit Varma]: there's a deeper crisis and that has to do with women. And I'll quote the most interesting

00:29:17.840 --> 00:29:22.480
[Amit Varma]: statistic of your series, which I, you know, I found in the first piece that you wrote in

00:29:22.480 --> 00:29:28.560
[Amit Varma]: the series on India Spent. Quote, in the first four months of 2017, a nugget of information went

00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:36.720
[Amit Varma]: by unnoticed. While jobs for men increased by 0.9 million, 2.4 million women fell off the employment

00:29:36.720 --> 00:29:43.520
[Amit Varma]: map, according to the CMIE. If the number of women who quit jobs in India between 2004-05

00:29:43.520 --> 00:29:50.880
[Amit Varma]: and 2011-12, the last year for which census data is available, was a city, it would be 19.6 million,

00:29:50.880 --> 00:29:57.600
[Amit Varma]: the third most populated city in the world after Shanghai and Beijing. And this, you know,

00:29:57.600 --> 00:30:01.360
[Amit Varma]: the first time I came across this, and of course, since then, I've come across this repeatedly,

00:30:01.360 --> 00:30:05.600
[Amit Varma]: including in your pieces where you've analysed it so well. And it just blew my mind that I'd

00:30:05.600 --> 00:30:09.360
[Amit Varma]: imagined that we've liberalised, we are progressing, there's globalisation, there's

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:14.320
[Amit Varma]: technology, more women should be working, and yet less women are working. Why is that?

00:30:14.320 --> 00:30:21.440
[Guest]: Absolutely true. And again, the unseen crisis, the unseen nation that you spoke about.

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:28.960
[Guest]: You know, we in media, we celebrate the exceptional. So the first woman firefighter,

00:30:28.960 --> 00:30:34.080
[Guest]: everybody is writing about her and she's getting awards and she's everywhere, she's on TV,

00:30:34.080 --> 00:30:40.560
[Guest]: she's being interviewed. The 19.6 million women who lost jobs in just that decade,

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:47.120
[Guest]: that trend has not followed. When I started doing the series, I was quoting 2011 census figures,

00:30:47.120 --> 00:30:53.200
[Guest]: and I was quoting the 2017 World Bank report, where women's labour force participation in

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:59.120
[Guest]: India was 27%. When I finished the series, and there are 12 articles, not nine, sorry for that

00:30:59.120 --> 00:31:02.320
[Amit Varma]: little correction. I'm so sorry, I just followed all the links from each of them. Yes, I think

00:31:02.320 --> 00:31:07.360
[Guest]: they got tired of putting up the links because, you know, it was the same. So anyway, when I

00:31:07.360 --> 00:31:13.680
[Guest]: finished the series a year later, the Economic Survey of 2018 had put women's labour force

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:20.080
[Guest]: participation at just 24%. In a city like Delhi, what is the labour force participation? Take a

00:31:20.080 --> 00:31:25.200
[Amit Varma]: guess. Roughly. 30%?

00:31:26.480 --> 00:31:28.400
[Guest]: 15%. 15%.

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:37.440
[Guest]: 15%. This is the capital city of India. And it is a mystery as to why this labour force,

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:43.440
[Guest]: why are women falling off the labour map at a time of rising education? And you know, of course,

00:31:43.440 --> 00:31:53.040
[Guest]: the great success stories of India is that women, girls now enrol into school, primary, secondary,

00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:59.280
[Guest]: as well as high school, at the same rate as men, as boys. There is no gender, we have bridged that

00:31:59.280 --> 00:32:05.200
[Guest]: gender gap. That is actually one of our great victories. Again, an unseen nation. I don't know

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:10.320
[Guest]: why the government has not gone to town talking about it, because it is rightfully a grand

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:13.040
[Guest]: achievement. This is primary and secondary education.

00:32:13.040 --> 00:32:18.000
[Guest]: Yes, there's a tiny gap. I mean, the last year's figures, I think there's a tiny gap of about

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:24.320
[Guest]: 1 point something percent in high school. But primary and secondary, there is no gender gap at

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:30.560
[Guest]: all. It's a remarkable achievement for any government where the gender gap has been so

00:32:30.560 --> 00:32:35.920
[Guest]: huge in education. So girls are in school, you know, for a variety of reasons. Governments are

00:32:35.920 --> 00:32:41.760
[Guest]: giving them cycles. There's the midday meal. I mean, these are all great game changers. And the

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:45.680
[Guest]: girls are in school. Let's not talk about quality of education, because it's the same quality of

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:53.200
[Guest]: education for girls and boys. Fertility rate is declining. We know that. Aspiration is rising.

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:59.680
[Guest]: We know that. So why are girls dropping out of the workforce? I mean, it's a huge mystery.

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:02.960
[Guest]: And why aren't we talking about it? It's one of those silent crises,

00:33:03.600 --> 00:33:10.240
[Guest]: which nobody wants to talk about, not governments, and not even women themselves.

00:33:10.240 --> 00:33:14.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's another startling statistic, which refers to justice from one of your pieces,

00:33:14.960 --> 00:33:21.440
[Amit Varma]: a quote, in rural India, 67% of girls who are graduates do not work. In towns and cities,

00:33:21.440 --> 00:33:24.800
[Amit Varma]: 68.3% of women who graduate don't have paid jobs.

00:33:24.800 --> 00:33:29.600
[Guest]: That's right. So the good news, of course, is that one reason why women are dropping out of

00:33:29.600 --> 00:33:35.280
[Guest]: the labor force is because they are in school. They're studying. And I have been to a university

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:40.640
[Guest]: in a rural area in Haryana, where girls from villages are even doing their PhD.

00:33:40.640 --> 00:33:46.880
[Guest]: But education has become an end in itself. You know, parents today are willing to say,

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:53.040
[Guest]: ha beta, padlo, padho, padho, padho. But after padhai, then what? After you do your MA,

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:58.720
[Guest]: you do your PhD. After PhD, then what? At what point do you start working? That message is not

00:33:58.720 --> 00:34:03.360
[Guest]: coming through. So nobody is really saying, no, you have to go out, you have to get careers,

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:08.640
[Guest]: you have to have jobs. We're not still telling our, or we might even be telling our daughters,

00:34:08.640 --> 00:34:13.920
[Guest]: you can have a job, but we're still not talking about having a career. A career as being defined

00:34:13.920 --> 00:34:18.800
[Guest]: as a job that you do for your whole life. You know, where you progress, where you go. So boys

00:34:18.800 --> 00:34:24.160
[Guest]: are being conditioned that, no, you've got to work. And this is the destiny of your life for

00:34:24.160 --> 00:34:28.640
[Guest]: the rest of your adult life, right? Girls are not being taught that. We are still telling girls,

00:34:28.640 --> 00:34:34.720
[Guest]: your priority is your family. Your priority is your husband, your children, your in-laws,

00:34:34.720 --> 00:34:42.880
[Guest]: the parents, the everything. Job you can do, but first do this. This is your natural job.

00:34:42.880 --> 00:34:49.440
[Amit Varma]: This is what you were born to do. That has to give. And this is again a finding I'm kind of

00:34:49.440 --> 00:34:55.760
[Amit Varma]: baffled by because not that they don't want their daughters to work. That's been an age old story.

00:34:55.760 --> 00:34:59.920
[Amit Varma]: But the fact that they then get asking them to study at all. I mean, because earlier, you know,

00:34:59.920 --> 00:35:04.080
[Amit Varma]: there was this conception that back in the day that you don't educate a girl too much because

00:35:04.080 --> 00:35:08.080
[Amit Varma]: she'll talk back to her husband and all of that. And now if they're encouraging them,

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:15.760
[Amit Varma]: and I don't get that. Is it kind of to keep them out of trouble's way? So they are,

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:20.240
[Guest]: I mean, I don't understand. It's to use our favorite Indian expression, not time pass.

00:35:23.680 --> 00:35:28.320
[Guest]: You don't want her to work. You don't want her to get into the job force because that may be

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:32.240
[Guest]: something that goes against her marriage. I'm not saying everybody's doing PhD. I mean,

00:35:32.240 --> 00:35:38.480
[Guest]: we're talking about a very small percentage, but there is no stigma anymore in education.

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:43.280
[Guest]: You know, so nobody is saying that don't study. I mean, it is accepted that your daughter will now

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:51.760
[Guest]: do at least up to class 12 and class 10. But after that, what happens? Why are we not telling

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:57.440
[Guest]: them or why are parents not saying, well, you need to work. And this is as important as having

00:35:57.440 --> 00:36:03.600
[Guest]: children and marriage and everything else. So in fact, Farzana Afridi, the economist, she says,

00:36:03.600 --> 00:36:07.600
[Guest]: you know, people talk about, economists talk about the motherhood penalty and this happens

00:36:07.600 --> 00:36:14.240
[Guest]: globally, right? You become a mom and you fall off the workforce. But Farzana Afridi talks about

00:36:14.240 --> 00:36:20.240
[Guest]: the marriage penalty. She says the first tumbling block is actually marriage. So there is a tiny

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:26.320
[Guest]: window where women might work. And that tiny window is between studies and marriage. Once they

00:36:26.320 --> 00:36:32.880
[Guest]: marry, workforce participation just declines. And the data is there. If you look at workforce

00:36:32.880 --> 00:36:38.720
[Guest]: participation of married women vis-a-vis single women and single women meaning before they're

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:45.360
[Guest]: married, if they were to become widowed, the workforce participation rate then shoots up.

00:36:45.360 --> 00:36:51.440
[Guest]: Single women actually do work, but single women after marriage. So if they're either divorced,

00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:57.200
[Guest]: abandoned or widowed, they are expected to work. Because then I guess also they don't have a

00:36:57.200 --> 00:37:02.240
[Amit Varma]: choice. It's almost like the spirit of Bombay. I mean, you have to do it. What else can you do?

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:06.560
[Guest]: You have to do it. So even farmer wives, for instance, the farmers who commit suicide,

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:14.000
[Guest]: their wives are not, very often they go back home. Very often, I have seen this myself,

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:19.600
[Guest]: they're not even given a place inside the house. They build a hut in the middle of the field

00:37:19.600 --> 00:37:26.000
[Guest]: and they are put into dehari or whatever it is that they can do. Then they are told very clearly

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:30.400
[Guest]: that we cannot afford to sit and feed you and your children. You are expected to work.

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:35.920
[Amit Varma]: So they become a resource of a different sort. Before, while they are married, they are looked at

00:37:35.920 --> 00:37:39.520
[Amit Varma]: as resources who will look after their husband and look after the house and all that. But when

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:43.200
[Amit Varma]: the husband isn't there and that function is redundant, hey, you're still a resource. You've

00:37:43.200 --> 00:37:48.480
[Amit Varma]: got to do something. You address a question in one of your pieces, which I'll kind of quote at you

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:54.160
[Amit Varma]: and let you elaborate on that, which is, quote, the 2011 National Sample Survey found that over

00:37:54.160 --> 00:38:00.080
[Amit Varma]: a third of women in urban India and half in rural areas who engage mainly in housework want a paying

00:38:00.080 --> 00:38:06.080
[Amit Varma]: job. So if women want jobs, why are they quitting? What's holding them back? Stop quote.

00:38:06.720 --> 00:38:13.680
[Guest]: Yeah. So what's holding them back? My very simple answer, if an unpopular answer is family.

00:38:13.680 --> 00:38:22.320
[Guest]: The structure of family is such that it imposes a tremendous burden on girls and on expectation

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:27.200
[Guest]: from girls. Where does this come from? This idea that girls must grow up to look after their

00:38:27.200 --> 00:38:32.160
[Guest]: husbands and cook the food and all of that. Where does this idea come from? It comes from

00:38:32.160 --> 00:38:37.760
[Guest]: the family. It's not coming from some external force. And it is true to a large extent of

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:44.240
[Guest]: everywhere in the world. When we talk about the burden of care work, it falls disproportionately

00:38:44.240 --> 00:38:50.480
[Guest]: on women. And there is not a single country in the world, not even the Scandinavian utopian

00:38:50.480 --> 00:38:56.800
[Guest]: societies, where the work is 50-50. There is an imbalance all over. Of course, in India,

00:38:56.800 --> 00:39:02.400
[Guest]: that imbalance is particularly bad. And depending on where women are living, they could be spending

00:39:02.400 --> 00:39:09.680
[Guest]: as much as five hours a day on care work. What is care work? It is the cooking, cleaning,

00:39:09.680 --> 00:39:16.480
[Guest]: caring for children and the elderly. It involves the fetching of firewood, the fetching of water.

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:22.880
[Guest]: Women spend hours just fetching water. It is their job. So where is the time? In fact,

00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:29.040
[Guest]: when people say women don't work, I take great exception to that statement, because women

00:39:29.040 --> 00:39:35.040
[Guest]: actually work. And if you were to factor in the work that is unpaid, the care work,

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:40.480
[Guest]: then women probably work far more than men. In fact, the figure in one of, again, I'm getting

00:39:40.480 --> 00:39:45.840
[Amit Varma]: this from one of your pieces, is that unpaid work, women in India do unpaid work for five hours or

00:39:45.840 --> 00:39:54.560
[Amit Varma]: 351.9 minutes a day. And men do it for 51.8 minutes a day. 51 sounds a lot. What do men

00:39:54.560 --> 00:39:59.600
[Guest]: do for 51 minutes? Oh, they do. So when I ask women, and I've asked a lot of women, including

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:04.960
[Guest]: in places like Bombay, I say, well, does your husband help or does your son help? And then they

00:40:04.960 --> 00:40:09.360
[Guest]: say, yeah, of course they help. And I'm like, what do they do? So they said, oh, both, you know,

00:40:09.360 --> 00:40:13.680
[Guest]: when I'm cooking, he plays with the children. So that's unpaid work. That's unpaid work,

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:19.920
[Guest]: according to the women. And you get the most astounding responses. So there was this one

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:25.440
[Guest]: woman I remember in Bombay, and I said, tell me your day. So she started telling me, she wakes up

00:40:25.440 --> 00:40:29.600
[Guest]: at 5am, there's water, you have to stand in line, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah. It goes on. Then she

00:40:29.600 --> 00:40:32.960
[Guest]: makes the lunch. Then she makes the dinner. I said, why can't you cook lunch and dinner at the

00:40:32.960 --> 00:40:39.440
[Guest]: same time? Just cook it once a day. And she was insulted. She said, my husband's not going to eat

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:44.880
[Guest]: basi khana. My children are not going to eat basi khana. So she's cooking twice a day,

00:40:44.880 --> 00:40:50.080
[Guest]: unquestioningly, you know, because the food must be made twice a day. So yeah, when the men work,

00:40:50.080 --> 00:40:56.800
[Guest]: the unpaid work, what does your son do? I asked, does he help you? Yes, he helps me. What does he

00:40:56.800 --> 00:41:03.360
[Guest]: do? If I need something, he runs to the market and gets it. So that's included in the care work.

00:41:03.360 --> 00:41:10.080
[Guest]: So regardless of what they do, it is pretty steep. It's one of the worst in the world.

00:41:10.080 --> 00:41:16.320
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, this kind of, like the man in this case, the husband who doesn't want basi

00:41:16.320 --> 00:41:21.440
[Amit Varma]: food is perhaps completely oblivious to what he's putting his wife through by making her cook twice

00:41:21.440 --> 00:41:25.520
[Guest]: a day. But it's a woman who doesn't want to give him basi food also. So this is the point that you

00:41:25.520 --> 00:41:32.000
[Guest]: were making about men and women. I mean, women are a part of the patriarchy as well. And there

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:37.440
[Guest]: are feminist men. So when you talk about the fight, the gender fight, the fight for gender

00:41:37.440 --> 00:41:43.360
[Guest]: equality, let's not forget, let's not forget Jyoti Singh Pandey's father, right? We're coming

00:41:43.360 --> 00:41:50.400
[Guest]: back to Jyoti Singh Pandey. He sold his ancestral land in his village because he wanted to educate

00:41:50.400 --> 00:41:56.720
[Guest]: his daughter. She wanted to be a physiotherapist and he had two sons, two younger sons after her.

00:41:57.440 --> 00:42:02.560
[Guest]: He never once said, I need money for your dowry. He never once said, I need money for your brother's

00:42:02.560 --> 00:42:06.800
[Guest]: education because they are going to rightfully look after me in my old age. She said, I want

00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:11.600
[Guest]: to be a physiotherapist. He sold the land to finance her education. So our greatest allies

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:18.000
[Guest]: can also be men. So patriarchy is about gender, but it need not always be gendered. You have

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:22.640
[Amit Varma]: feminist men and you have patriarchal women. That's a great point. And another sort of

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:28.880
[Amit Varma]: point you made about why more women don't work is agency, where again, to quote from you,

00:42:29.440 --> 00:42:34.560
[Amit Varma]: the 2011 Human Development Survey finds that a sizable number of women need to take permission

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:39.680
[Amit Varma]: from a family member to even go to the market or healthcare, said Rohini Pandey of Howard

00:42:39.680 --> 00:42:44.640
[Amit Varma]: Kennedy School. And again, you quote her, in the end, it's pretty difficult to look for a job if

00:42:44.640 --> 00:42:47.840
[Amit Varma]: you can't leave the house alone. Stop quote. Absolutely.

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:52.640
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, women are part of this. It's even, it's a girl's mother who will tell her that

00:42:52.640 --> 00:42:58.800
[Guest]: no, you can't go alone. Or the mother-in-law. Yeah. Somebody needs to go with you. Sometimes,

00:42:58.800 --> 00:43:04.080
[Guest]: in fact, in Bihar, I met women and sometimes they are accompanied to the market with some

00:43:04.080 --> 00:43:08.720
[Guest]: small boy, a five-year-old boy, you know, they're holding that little boy, but that boy must go with

00:43:08.720 --> 00:43:14.800
[Amit Varma]: them to the market because they cannot go alone. Wow. And another sort of thing that comes in the

00:43:14.800 --> 00:43:20.960
[Amit Varma]: way of women working is the sort of disincentives for employers to employ women. Like again,

00:43:20.960 --> 00:43:25.440
[Amit Varma]: a quote from one of your pieces, Medha Oniyal, Program Director of the Pratham Institute was

00:43:25.440 --> 00:43:31.680
[Amit Varma]: more blunt. And here you quote the lady, when you have women on the payroll, you are legally

00:43:31.680 --> 00:43:36.800
[Amit Varma]: required to provide facilities like a creche. So a lot of employers have a clear mandate of

00:43:36.800 --> 00:43:41.360
[Amit Varma]: not hiring women. Stop quote. And these sort of disincentives even come through, say,

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:47.680
[Amit Varma]: well-intentioned policies like maternity leave, mandated maternity leave and all where sort of

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:52.080
[Amit Varma]: these disincentives as such exist. What's your feeling on that?

00:43:52.080 --> 00:43:56.560
[Guest]: So let me tell you what my problem with maternity leave is. When the government,

00:43:56.560 --> 00:44:01.760
[Guest]: the previous government increased maternity leave, of course, everybody cheered, listen, six months,

00:44:01.760 --> 00:44:08.320
[Guest]: why not? You know, it's great. But when you mandate six months for women and nothing for men,

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:12.640
[Guest]: I mean, in the private sector, there are some enlightened, quote unquote,

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:17.680
[Guest]: enlightened companies that will give you 10 days off. What is your messaging?

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:25.120
[Guest]: Your messaging is that this is your job. A man's job is nothing. So who's again,

00:44:25.120 --> 00:44:30.560
[Guest]: you're reinforcing the stereotype of what is women's work? See, what is my objection to unpaid

00:44:30.560 --> 00:44:35.360
[Guest]: care work? My objection to unpaid care work is that when you're spending five hours a day

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:39.920
[Guest]: fetching water or fetching firewood, where is the time to go and do paid work?

00:44:39.920 --> 00:44:44.800
[Guest]: So you are working, you're just not getting paid for it, right? When you bring in a mandate,

00:44:44.800 --> 00:44:52.160
[Guest]: when you increase maternity leave by six months, what happens? Small and medium enterprises tell

00:44:52.160 --> 00:44:58.880
[Guest]: themselves, there is a certain demographic that I will not hire. A young, about to be married,

00:44:58.880 --> 00:45:04.000
[Guest]: marriageable age or recently married woman with no children, I can't afford to hire her because I

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:08.400
[Guest]: can't afford to give her six months leave. Right? You have to understand. So is the government

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:13.440
[Guest]: subsidizing a part of that leave? I'd like to know that. And my point is, why do we not? We have a

00:45:13.440 --> 00:45:18.720
[Guest]: model in the Scandinavian countries where you have, it's called parental leave. So it's three

00:45:18.720 --> 00:45:23.440
[Guest]: months for moms, three months for dads, and then the remaining three months, you choose which one.

00:45:23.440 --> 00:45:28.640
[Guest]: And the three months for dads cannot be transferred to the moms. And I was shocked. I was on a TV

00:45:28.640 --> 00:45:35.200
[Guest]: debate talking about this, my objection to maternity leave. And Naina Lal Kidwai was

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:41.840
[Guest]: on the panel with me and said, oh, you know, if you give men paternity leave, they will all go

00:45:41.840 --> 00:45:49.440
[Guest]: off to play golf. And I found that patronizing to the extreme, because you're basically saying that

00:45:49.440 --> 00:45:55.840
[Guest]: men are shits and they will do nothing. You don't give them a chance. And if you mandate it and say

00:45:55.840 --> 00:46:01.600
[Guest]: this leave cannot be transferred to women, then maybe they won't. So what happens when women

00:46:02.880 --> 00:46:08.320
[Guest]: get this? And let's remember, we're talking about the formal sector that only hires what,

00:46:08.320 --> 00:46:13.840
[Guest]: 4% women? The informal sector, we're not even talking about where the vast majority of women

00:46:13.840 --> 00:46:19.520
[Guest]: work. So in the formal sector as well, when a woman takes six months leave, let's say she's

00:46:19.520 --> 00:46:25.680
[Guest]: in a big company like an IBM, right? And when she comes back, she suddenly finds that she's

00:46:25.680 --> 00:46:31.360
[Guest]: redundant. She suddenly finds that, and I know this from personal experience, talking to young

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:36.720
[Guest]: women in the IT sector, they say, oh, you know, when we came back from work, from maternity leave,

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:43.040
[Guest]: six months, which is allowed to us. And we came back and we said, our bosses say, look, don't do

00:46:43.040 --> 00:46:48.640
[Guest]: this. This assignment is really a tough assignment. So the women, so this is another interesting

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:54.720
[Guest]: statistic, right? NASSCOM did a survey. At entry level, women in tech are 51%.

00:46:56.080 --> 00:47:02.640
[Guest]: But overall, it's only 36%. And at the senior leadership level, it dwindles to single

00:47:02.640 --> 00:47:09.120
[Guest]: percentages. The same newsroom example I gave you about, women are there all across the newsroom,

00:47:09.120 --> 00:47:14.240
[Guest]: but in the corner offices, they're only men. So what happens at middle management level

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:19.920
[Guest]: is that that is when your kids, you start having children, or the parents grow older,

00:47:19.920 --> 00:47:24.080
[Guest]: or the in-laws, you know, there's an in-law who's suddenly incapacitated, has to be taken to the

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:31.360
[Guest]: hospital. That burden falls on women and not on men. So when a woman often comes back from maternity

00:47:31.360 --> 00:47:35.920
[Guest]: leave, her boss will tell her, you're a very nice, lovely man, the supervisor, and he's saying, no,

00:47:35.920 --> 00:47:41.360
[Guest]: don't do this assignment. It's a tough assignment, the long hours. So the women lose out on

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:45.600
[Guest]: opportunities. They lose out on the foreign assignments, on the challenging assignments,

00:47:45.600 --> 00:47:49.440
[Guest]: because within the office, there is a culture that says, you can't do it, you're a mom.

00:47:51.360 --> 00:47:56.720
[Amit Varma]: Right. And I should at this point say that, you know, two of the editors I work with as a columnist

00:47:56.720 --> 00:48:00.720
[Amit Varma]: are both women. So there are some women in the corner office, but journalism is very much the

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:06.320
[Amit Varma]: exception in that, in that sense that I think the rate of women in journalism must be way higher.

00:48:06.320 --> 00:48:07.920
[Guest]: Yes. Than other professions.

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:15.600
[Guest]: Like journalism, entertainment, you know, so you do have a higher proportion of women. And yes,

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:21.600
[Guest]: as the generations proceed, as we started talking about how every generation had its own battle. So

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:27.840
[Guest]: today's battle is going to shift to the corner rooms. The battle is not in some sectors and

00:48:27.840 --> 00:48:33.680
[Guest]: amongst a certain demographic, the battle is retaining talent. So in 51% women are joining

00:48:33.680 --> 00:48:39.200
[Guest]: tech. So they're coming into the workforce, but somewhere, somewhere they just fall off

00:48:39.200 --> 00:48:45.920
[Guest]: because there is a glass ceiling that remains intact. And I've spoken to so many women as well

00:48:45.920 --> 00:48:53.120
[Guest]: as men, more women than men, of course, when you look about workplace design, you have to ask

00:48:53.120 --> 00:48:59.200
[Guest]: yourself who designed the workplace. It's not designed by women. It's designed by men. Men are

00:48:59.200 --> 00:49:03.920
[Guest]: very happy. Men have only one job. They have to go to work and they have to be brilliant. That is it.

00:49:03.920 --> 00:49:09.840
[Guest]: They don't have to worry about who's putting the kids to bed or who's taking mom to the hospital

00:49:09.840 --> 00:49:14.960
[Guest]: for her checkup or any of that. They don't have to worry. They just get into work. Someone is

00:49:14.960 --> 00:49:20.560
[Guest]: looking after them. And in fact, in Lean In, Sheryl Sandberg talks about the fact that every

00:49:20.560 --> 00:49:28.320
[Guest]: successful CEO has a wife who's propping him up. Every successful woman CEO does not necessarily

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:33.520
[Guest]: have that husband who's doing the same job. I mean, how many husbands do we have who will say

00:49:33.520 --> 00:49:37.680
[Guest]: they'll give up their careers and they'll tell their wives, go out and be brilliant. I'll take

00:49:37.680 --> 00:49:43.760
[Guest]: care of the house, or I'll at least share an equal share of this burden. They're very few.

00:49:43.760 --> 00:49:49.520
[Guest]: And when men do it, they're heroes. You say, wow, look at this guy. What a super dad. When a mom

00:49:49.520 --> 00:49:56.080
[Guest]: quits her job, she's just another mom. It's no big deal. No. And in fact, you mentioned workplace

00:49:56.080 --> 00:50:02.560
[Amit Varma]: design. I'd written an editorial at around the time Me Too happened. And it's interesting that

00:50:02.560 --> 00:50:08.400
[Amit Varma]: if you consider the air conditioning in offices, air conditioning was essentially, it was

00:50:09.040 --> 00:50:14.560
[Amit Varma]: regularized in offices in the 50s and 60s when offices were mostly full of men and the optimum

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:19.920
[Amit Varma]: temperature then was fixed at whatever it was. Now, since then, we've discovered that men tend

00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:25.040
[Amit Varma]: to be comfortable at a particular temperature and women need a slightly higher temperature

00:50:25.040 --> 00:50:28.880
[Amit Varma]: to be comfortable. So in the normal office designed for a man, if the man is comfortable,

00:50:28.880 --> 00:50:34.000
[Amit Varma]: the woman will inevitably be cold. And this is something modern offices have simply not taken

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:40.400
[Guest]: into account. Well, I wish the problem was just air conditioning. But it's not. When I'm talking

00:50:40.400 --> 00:50:47.520
[Guest]: about workplace design, I'm talking, look, women are capable of working very hard. On construction

00:50:47.520 --> 00:50:55.120
[Guest]: sites, you'll see that women can carry headloads of up to 60 kilos. But women want to work very

00:50:55.120 --> 00:51:01.200
[Guest]: differently from men. Women need breaks. A lot of women say, I need to be home at lunchtime because

00:51:01.200 --> 00:51:05.600
[Guest]: I need to cook with an invalid parent or my children are coming home from school and I need

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:12.080
[Guest]: to get food on the table. I can come back. So that's why women, I mean, for me, freelancing was

00:51:12.880 --> 00:51:17.840
[Guest]: liberating because I did not have to spend time commuting. I did not have to spend time in,

00:51:17.840 --> 00:51:24.240
[Guest]: you know, frankly, pretty useless meetings. It freed me up and I was able to work. So I could

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:29.280
[Guest]: work early in the morning. I could work late at night when my kids are grown up now, but when

00:51:29.280 --> 00:51:35.920
[Guest]: they were younger, you put the kids to bed, you work. So women can work very hard and are very

00:51:35.920 --> 00:51:41.600
[Guest]: dedicated and have a certain discipline. And then, of course, you have workplaces designed by men

00:51:42.320 --> 00:51:49.360
[Guest]: designing things like off-sites. My God, I mean, women, I can tell you, hate off-sites. They hate

00:51:49.360 --> 00:51:56.160
[Guest]: off-sites because it takes them away. It means it's a logistics nightmare because you have to plan

00:51:56.160 --> 00:52:00.160
[Guest]: food, you have to put food in the freezer, you have to make sure who's going to take the kids

00:52:00.160 --> 00:52:06.560
[Guest]: to school, blah, blah, blah. Or let's take another example, networking after drinks. How many women

00:52:06.560 --> 00:52:11.760
[Guest]: really have the freedom to do that? So it's very well for Sheryl Sandberg and others to say,

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:17.600
[Guest]: lean in. How much are you going to lean? And you can lean and lean and lean with all your might.

00:52:17.600 --> 00:52:24.320
[Guest]: But ultimately, workplaces also need to recognize that if they are to retain female talent, then

00:52:24.320 --> 00:52:31.040
[Guest]: they need to lean in too. They need to lean out. And in fact, the point you made about, you know,

00:52:31.040 --> 00:52:34.880
[Amit Varma]: networking after work hours and all, and just thinking aloud, it strikes me as another reason

00:52:34.880 --> 00:52:39.840
[Amit Varma]: of many, many reasons that women don't reach the corner office because rising in corporate life

00:52:39.840 --> 00:52:46.240
[Amit Varma]: requires so much networking and schmoozing and all of that. And, you know, women spend less time

00:52:46.240 --> 00:52:51.840
[Amit Varma]: networking perhaps and more focused on their jobs. And they will, of course, be very wary of schmoozing.

00:52:51.840 --> 00:52:58.240
[Guest]: Yeah. So all of these become impediments. Yeah, I see myself, you're taking me back to the days

00:52:58.240 --> 00:53:02.880
[Guest]: when I wanted to pick up my bag at five o'clock. I was willing to make the sacrifice. I was taking

00:53:02.880 --> 00:53:09.520
[Guest]: the pain of earning half of what everybody else was earning, even though I was doing as much work.

00:53:10.240 --> 00:53:17.680
[Guest]: And, but I need to be home. That was it. That was a non-negotiable for me. Now, if you tell me

00:53:17.680 --> 00:53:21.840
[Guest]: that, well, you have to go out, you have to meet contacts, you have to meet sources, you have to

00:53:21.840 --> 00:53:26.800
[Guest]: have drinks, you have to go for off sites, you have to do all these bonding exercises so that

00:53:26.800 --> 00:53:32.720
[Amit Varma]: you can bond as a team. I mean, it is painful. We'll take a quick commercial break now. And

00:53:32.720 --> 00:53:36.240
[Amit Varma]: after we return, we'll talk about your favorite state, Haryana.

00:53:37.600 --> 00:53:41.440
[Unknown]: Hey, everybody, welcome to another great week on the IBM Podcast Network. You know,

00:53:41.440 --> 00:53:44.960
[Unknown]: the greatest place on earth to work on. If you're interested in working with us,

00:53:44.960 --> 00:53:48.480
[Unknown]: please do send us your resume at careersinthisbox.com. We're looking for people in business

