[Unknown]: career and how to deal with conflicts in any industry. And with that, let's get you on with

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:43.040
[Amit Varma]: your show. Welcome back to The Seen and The Unseen. I'm chatting with Namita Bhandare about

00:55:43.040 --> 00:55:49.520
[Amit Varma]: women at work or in general, the state of women in India today. One of the things that fascinated

00:55:49.520 --> 00:55:53.280
[Amit Varma]: me about your many pieces, both your series on India Spend and then you've written separate

00:55:53.280 --> 00:55:59.440
[Amit Varma]: pieces in Hindu Sun Times about it over the years, is sort of looking at Haryana as a case study in

00:55:59.440 --> 00:56:05.360
[Amit Varma]: particular. And again, I'll quote some figures from your pieces. You point out that Haryana has

00:56:05.360 --> 00:56:13.440
[Amit Varma]: famously a very low sex ratio, 836 girls for every 1000 boys at birth among children born in the last

00:56:13.440 --> 00:56:19.840
[Amit Varma]: five years. This was in a data in 2015-16. And the national average at this time was 919, which

00:56:19.840 --> 00:56:25.920
[Amit Varma]: itself is abysmal. I mean, just as we talk about, say, an invisible country, you can also talk about

00:56:25.920 --> 00:56:32.480
[Amit Varma]: a lost country of the missing women as the famous phrase goes. And to quote from one of your pieces,

00:56:32.480 --> 00:56:38.480
[Amit Varma]: quote, in 2015, for instance, Haryana reported the country's largest number of gang rapes,

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:43.840
[Amit Varma]: 1.6 for every 1 lakh women, according to National Crime Records Bureau data. It had the second

00:56:43.840 --> 00:56:49.280
[Amit Varma]: highest rate of dowry deaths at 1.9 per lakh population, and the third highest rate in

00:56:49.280 --> 00:56:57.200
[Amit Varma]: stalking women at 2.7 cases per lakh population. And you've spent a lot of time in Haryana. Tell

00:56:57.200 --> 00:57:00.400
[Amit Varma]: us about some of the sort of insights you've got about what's going on there.

00:57:00.400 --> 00:57:07.440
[Guest]: You know, when you think about dystopian horror stories, it's almost like a black mirror

00:57:07.440 --> 00:57:15.200
[Guest]: episode, right? What happens in villages that kill off its daughters? You have women being

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:20.240
[Guest]: trafficked from the Northeast and from other states, poorer states into Haryana. Haryana is

00:57:20.240 --> 00:57:26.560
[Guest]: a rich state. So it does poorly on gender indices, but is otherwise a prosperous state with agriculture

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:33.280
[Guest]: and so on. And so they can afford to buy. So I have met women who are being imported in,

00:57:33.280 --> 00:57:39.040
[Guest]: they're being trafficked really, you know, for marriage, sometimes being shared between two

00:57:39.040 --> 00:57:47.680
[Guest]: brothers, really functioning as sex slaves in a state that has chosen to kill off its daughters.

00:57:48.400 --> 00:57:53.200
[Guest]: And this is not something, I mean, you're seeing this horror spread. I mean,

00:57:53.200 --> 00:57:59.280
[Guest]: Beti Bachao began in Haryana. It was launched, if you remember, by Narendra Modi from Haryana

00:57:59.280 --> 00:58:06.400
[Guest]: for a reason. And that was to, you know, the acceptability of daughters. Recently,

00:58:06.400 --> 00:58:13.120
[Guest]: you must have read in the news, Uttarakhand, 130 villages that have not seen the birth of a girl

00:58:13.120 --> 00:58:21.680
[Guest]: for the last few months, right? You know, Amartya Sen wrote about the missing women, I mean,

00:58:21.680 --> 00:58:26.960
[Guest]: missing girls. You're seeing this happen. This is not an academic or a theoretical discussion.

00:58:26.960 --> 00:58:32.000
[Guest]: You are seeing it happen. What happens when a state does not value its girls?

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:37.680
[Guest]: So when a state does not value its girls, you will have a very high incidence of crime,

00:58:37.680 --> 00:58:41.920
[Guest]: because who's going to speak up? Who is speaking up for the rights of these women?

00:58:41.920 --> 00:58:47.120
[Guest]: I mean, you've killed off the women, right? So you have very high crime rate, you have otherwise

00:58:47.120 --> 00:58:54.480
[Guest]: very poor gender indices. But it is like all of India, Haryana is also filled with contradictions.

00:58:54.480 --> 00:58:59.120
[Guest]: So one of the things that you will find in Haryana, a lot of our sports women,

00:58:59.120 --> 00:59:06.080
[Guest]: our athletes are coming from Haryana, from this state where ghoonghat is like an accepted norm.

00:59:06.640 --> 00:59:12.880
[Guest]: And I remember there was a big furor because one of the state magazines issued by the state

00:59:12.880 --> 00:59:18.880
[Guest]: government, I mean, the headline was ghoonghat ki something aan baan hamari desh ki shaan.

00:59:18.880 --> 00:59:23.920
[Guest]: You know, ghoonghat was desh ki shaan. And I have been to panchayat elections where women

00:59:23.920 --> 00:59:27.440
[Guest]: are campaigning in ghoonghat and you can't tell who's the candidate because they're all looking

00:59:27.440 --> 00:59:33.840
[Guest]: the same. Because they've all covered their faces up to their knees, like ghoonghat is literally

00:59:33.840 --> 00:59:40.320
[Guest]: down to their knees. And yet you have this, the Fogart sisters, I mean, rough contact sport like

00:59:40.320 --> 00:59:49.200
[Guest]: wrestling, you know, and I think part of it comes from the fact that the desire for a government job.

00:59:49.760 --> 00:59:54.560
[Guest]: So parents feel that this is their ticket. So you will allow your daughter to play this sport

00:59:54.560 --> 00:59:58.320
[Guest]: in the hope that she'll get a sports quota and get a government job.

00:59:58.320 --> 01:00:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And the government job, as you've pointed out, is considered more respectable for them.

01:00:01.920 --> 01:00:08.560
[Guest]: Absolutely. Private sector jobs in Haryana are absolutely looked down upon. And the Jindals

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:14.080
[Guest]: have set up a steel factory. And I had gone and visited there. And there were a few women working

01:00:14.080 --> 01:00:20.320
[Guest]: and right on the factory floor, you know, so this was very revolutionary for Haryana. Most of them

01:00:20.320 --> 01:00:25.360
[Guest]: were actually unmarried. So they were in that little window that I mentioned between education

01:00:25.360 --> 01:00:30.000
[Guest]: and marriage. And one or two were engaged to be married. And you know, they were very clear

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:34.800
[Guest]: that shadi ke baad, it depends on what our husband says. And we know what he will say.

01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:38.720
[Guest]: I'm doing this for pocket money. You know, that was the excuse.

01:00:38.720 --> 01:00:43.280
[Amit Varma]: I actually have another theory about how this whole thing of women in sport kicked off in

01:00:43.280 --> 01:00:49.840
[Amit Varma]: Haryana. I done a feature story on Sakshi Malik a few years ago after the Olympics. And the trend

01:00:49.840 --> 01:00:55.120
[Amit Varma]: of women entering wrestling really began in about 1997 when there was this legendary coach called

01:00:55.120 --> 01:01:02.160
[Amit Varma]: Chandgi Ram. And Chandgi Ram was a famous wrestler himself. And he didn't have sons. And in 1997,

01:01:02.160 --> 01:01:07.440
[Amit Varma]: the Olympic Committee announced that from 2004, there would be women's wrestling in the Olympics

01:01:07.440 --> 01:01:11.600
[Amit Varma]: for the first time. And he saw that as an opportunity to get an Olympic medal for his

01:01:11.600 --> 01:01:16.960
[Amit Varma]: family and therefore trained his daughter Sonika Kalikaraman, who became an accomplished wrestler

01:01:16.960 --> 01:01:22.480
[Amit Varma]: herself and Mahavir Phogat from there, who was one of Chandgi Ram's assistants, if I remember,

01:01:22.480 --> 01:01:26.560
[Amit Varma]: trained his daughters. So even the root of that, which seems like empowerment,

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:29.360
[Amit Varma]: so many women in sport, even the root of that is male ego.

01:01:29.360 --> 01:01:36.320
[Guest]: Yeah. But if the result is that women are coming forward, I wouldn't quibble about that. I'm happy

01:01:36.320 --> 01:01:42.240
[Guest]: with male ego. And thank God that there were no portable ultrasound machines as there are now

01:01:42.240 --> 01:01:48.080
[Guest]: going literally into technology is being used. So, you know, maybe there would have been sons

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:54.080
[Guest]: if these ultrasound, portable ultrasound machines were going into every village

01:01:54.080 --> 01:01:58.560
[Guest]: at the time. But because there were no sons, these girls were allowed to come up. Yes,

01:01:58.560 --> 01:02:03.920
[Guest]: I get your point about it being a double-edged sword, but look at it from the other side,

01:02:03.920 --> 01:02:07.760
[Amit Varma]: at least they came up. At least girls today have role models. I mean, another point you made in

01:02:07.760 --> 01:02:14.160
[Amit Varma]: your series was about how when a woman works, it is not only that that one woman has a job and

01:02:14.160 --> 01:02:18.320
[Amit Varma]: she's working, it has a huge number of knock-on effects around her. Tell me a bit about that.

01:02:18.320 --> 01:02:23.760
[Guest]: Most of all, on her own standing, on her own self-esteem, on her own sense of who she is

01:02:23.760 --> 01:02:30.320
[Guest]: within the family, she suddenly gets a certain enhanced status because she's bringing in money,

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:37.360
[Guest]: she's bringing in prestige, she definitely gets a say in household decisions. She's a person,

01:02:37.360 --> 01:02:44.880
[Guest]: she's not just the roti provider or the child nurturer, you know, she is a person with a job

01:02:44.880 --> 01:02:50.320
[Guest]: and an identity. So I think that is something that is very, very important when women work.

01:02:50.320 --> 01:02:55.920
[Guest]: Let's forget about GDP and what it does to the economy. And of course, she becomes a role model

01:02:55.920 --> 01:03:02.000
[Guest]: for her daughters. The daughters of an employed mom are more likely to be employed themselves,

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:07.920
[Guest]: you know, because they accept that as normal. The sons see their moms going out to work.

01:03:07.920 --> 01:03:13.040
[Guest]: And so they say, well, you know, it's okay if our wives do the same. So it is a virtuous cycle. I

01:03:13.040 --> 01:03:19.440
[Guest]: don't see a downside to it at all, except of course, a downside to the woman's own sense of

01:03:19.440 --> 01:03:25.440
[Guest]: stress and managing the hundred things that she must multitask in order to get out of the house

01:03:25.440 --> 01:03:30.800
[Amit Varma]: to work. And despite this virtuous cycle, you know, women's participation in the labor force

01:03:30.800 --> 01:03:35.520
[Amit Varma]: is going down. And I meant to ask you a question earlier, well, we were talking about that,

01:03:35.520 --> 01:03:40.000
[Amit Varma]: but I forgot. So I'll ask that and then we'll go back to Haryana, which is about, you know,

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Claudia Golden, you must be familiar with her work, wrote about this famous U-shaped curve,

01:03:44.240 --> 01:03:49.520
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, as countries grow more advanced in the technology scale, less women work,

01:03:49.520 --> 01:03:54.960
[Amit Varma]: but then that changes as again, more women work. Does that curve apply to us? Are we at the low

01:03:54.960 --> 01:03:59.200
[Guest]: end of that curve or is something else happening entirely? So I don't have a crystal ball and I

01:03:59.200 --> 01:04:05.040
[Guest]: don't think anybody does. So we were definitely at the downward trend of the U-curve and we're

01:04:05.040 --> 01:04:10.320
[Guest]: going on sliding, you know, as you mentioned, demonetization, everybody made such a noise,

01:04:10.320 --> 01:04:16.480
[Guest]: you know, the headlines in every paper about job loss. Nobody pointed out the fact that the job

01:04:16.480 --> 01:04:23.520
[Guest]: loss was entirely amongst women. 0.9 men actually came into jobs after the first four months of

01:04:23.520 --> 01:04:29.280
[Guest]: demonetization. It was the women who lost jobs. So somehow again, it's a silent crisis that we

01:04:29.280 --> 01:04:36.320
[Guest]: don't see. And it is going on sliding, you know, down from 27 down to 25%. We don't know where the

01:04:36.320 --> 01:04:41.600
[Guest]: slide will end and when we'll bounce back. There is no way of telling when that will happen. We do

01:04:41.600 --> 01:04:47.360
[Guest]: have a jobs crisis. And I would like to just mention over here that it's almost as if jobs

01:04:47.360 --> 01:04:52.800
[Guest]: have become the new banana. What do I mean by that? I mean that in the old days, you often heard

01:04:52.800 --> 01:04:58.560
[Guest]: these stories about if a family is very poor and they had one banana, they would give it to the son,

01:04:58.560 --> 01:05:05.040
[Guest]: right? Not to the daughters. So jobs are that new banana. So within families, and I will not

01:05:05.040 --> 01:05:11.440
[Guest]: take the name of a minister from my favorite state of Haryana. It's not my favorite state.

01:05:11.440 --> 01:05:15.360
[Amit Varma]: It's just a state I've traveled to a lot. It's totally your favorite state. We're on the record.

01:05:15.360 --> 01:05:21.680
[Guest]: Oh, please come on. The gender record is awful. Appalling. Really appalling. And this minister

01:05:21.680 --> 01:05:28.400
[Guest]: told me, he says, Why are you doing so much women's labor force participation? If women

01:05:28.400 --> 01:05:35.440
[Guest]: get jobs, where will men go? So you must understand politically, why is it that political

01:05:35.440 --> 01:05:40.400
[Guest]: parties, you know, they don't, when political parties talk about women's empowerment, what are

01:05:40.400 --> 01:05:45.680
[Guest]: they talking about? CCTV footage? You know, crime rate? That's all they talk about. Nobody talks

01:05:45.680 --> 01:05:51.680
[Guest]: about jobs for women. And the reason why they don't talk about it is because they realize that,

01:05:51.680 --> 01:05:58.640
[Guest]: you know, when a man loses his job, he will come out on the street and agitate. 19.6, let's imagine

01:05:58.640 --> 01:06:06.720
[Guest]: 19.6 million men lost jobs in just a decade. Would there be such silence in the media amongst

01:06:06.720 --> 01:06:11.920
[Guest]: social groups, amongst feminist groups, amongst, I mean, in every sector, there is nothing,

01:06:11.920 --> 01:06:17.440
[Guest]: there is silence. Because where are those 19 points? I'll tell you one of the most difficult

01:06:17.440 --> 01:06:22.720
[Guest]: things that I faced while doing the series is finding women who had quit jobs. Because when

01:06:22.720 --> 01:06:30.080
[Guest]: a woman quits her job, she just melts into her kitchen. You cannot find these 19.6 million women,

01:06:30.080 --> 01:06:35.200
[Guest]: they're not in Jantar Mantar protesting, the men would have brought the governments down,

01:06:35.200 --> 01:06:41.200
[Guest]: successive governments down of 19.6 million men, it would have been a massive crisis on the front

01:06:41.200 --> 01:06:46.720
[Guest]: page of every newspaper and on the top of talk shows and on every TV channels.

01:06:46.720 --> 01:06:50.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's a very evocative and moving phrase melts into her kitchen. You know, I remember

01:06:50.960 --> 01:06:55.120
[Amit Varma]: this column last year by a columnist, I won't name her, but it kind of made me very angry,

01:06:55.120 --> 01:06:59.680
[Amit Varma]: where the column basically made the argument that it's fine if women don't work and they do

01:06:59.680 --> 01:07:04.480
[Amit Varma]: the unpaid work they do at home, because that is more optimal for society, which really pissed me

01:07:04.480 --> 01:07:09.200
[Amit Varma]: off. And I was editing Pragati at that time, I got one of my colleagues Devika Khet to write a

01:07:09.200 --> 01:07:15.440
[Amit Varma]: piece about that, because sort of rebutting that and that seems to me to be an analog of the kind

01:07:15.440 --> 01:07:20.560
[Amit Varma]: of argument you once heard and still hear sometimes in the context of caste, where even Gandhi made

01:07:20.560 --> 01:07:24.720
[Amit Varma]: the argument once that there is a purpose for the caste system and is good for society that

01:07:24.720 --> 01:07:30.480
[Amit Varma]: it's like that and everyone has the roles that they must play. And how does one respond to

01:07:30.480 --> 01:07:37.040
[Guest]: arguments like this? Oh, that is such bullshit. It really is. You know, this whole business of how,

01:07:37.680 --> 01:07:43.120
[Guest]: when women actually you have men, male economists and economists, I mean, saying basically,

01:07:43.120 --> 01:07:49.280
[Guest]: oh, women dropping out of the workforce is actually a good thing, because this means that

01:07:49.280 --> 01:07:54.640
[Guest]: A, the economy is progressing. So the U-curve syndrome that you spoke about, and B, this is

01:07:54.640 --> 01:07:59.920
[Guest]: pitched as a wonderful luxury for women. Why do you want to work? Why do you want to rush in the

01:07:59.920 --> 01:08:05.600
[Guest]: metro for a job? You can sit at home, relax. And make food twice a day. Because your husband doesn't

01:08:05.600 --> 01:08:13.200
[Guest]: want to eat basi khana. It is pitched as a luxury, as something that is aspirational,

01:08:13.200 --> 01:08:19.120
[Guest]: and as a step forward for women. You know, motherhood is endowed with such a lot of

01:08:20.080 --> 01:08:25.280
[Guest]: sublime and this, you know, everywhere in the popular culture, if you look at ads,

01:08:25.280 --> 01:08:30.640
[Guest]: you work with an ad agency. For eight months, 25 years ago, don't hold it against me.

01:08:30.640 --> 01:08:36.000
[Guest]: And you have these, you know, butterflies and mother's love and mother's care. And,

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:40.800
[Guest]: you know, it's like this noble, you know, my God, being a mother is the greatest thing any

01:08:40.800 --> 01:08:46.640
[Guest]: woman can do. I mean, why is not fatherhood endowed with that same, some of that same nobility?

01:08:46.640 --> 01:08:52.560
[Guest]: So a woman who says, well, I would rather have a career than sit at home and look after my children,

01:08:53.200 --> 01:08:58.080
[Guest]: you know, is a very, very bad woman. She's the woman we fear the most.

01:08:58.080 --> 01:09:02.560
[Guest]: We do not approve of that woman who says, I'd rather go to work than sit at home,

01:09:03.360 --> 01:09:08.560
[Amit Varma]: looking after my babies. And something else I'd want to talk about is family values. So,

01:09:08.560 --> 01:09:13.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, I was chatting today with a friend of mine. And he said that one of the great problems

01:09:13.280 --> 01:09:17.440
[Amit Varma]: in America today, one of the great social problems is a breakdown of family values.

01:09:17.440 --> 01:09:21.280
[Amit Varma]: And there's no phrase I hate more than that. I mean, I just thought that the very problem

01:09:21.280 --> 01:09:28.640
[Guest]: with India is bloody family values. Do you agree? I do. I do agree. Unpopular as this may make

01:09:28.640 --> 01:09:35.280
[Guest]: both of us. The family, look, families, as we said, there are families and families. Jyoti Singh

01:09:35.280 --> 01:09:41.200
[Guest]: Pandey's father is my role model, you know, a man who can sell his, but how many fathers are there

01:09:41.200 --> 01:09:47.520
[Guest]: like that? It is so, when we talk, when I say that, what is holding women back? Why are women

01:09:47.520 --> 01:09:51.920
[Guest]: falling off the workforce? The good news, the good reason why some of them are falling off

01:09:51.920 --> 01:09:56.080
[Guest]: the workforce is because they're in education rather than in employment. Fine. That's the

01:09:56.080 --> 01:10:01.440
[Guest]: good news. But what is the other reason? And the main other reason, you know, when you say patriarchy,

01:10:01.440 --> 01:10:08.560
[Guest]: patriarchy sounds like this wonderful, long word that masks a very ugly reality of Indian families,

01:10:08.560 --> 01:10:14.560
[Guest]: because it is families that impose stereotypical roles, stereotyping on sons and daughters. This

01:10:14.560 --> 01:10:20.800
[Guest]: is a girl's job. This is a boy's job. When a girl wants to go out to work, she must take the

01:10:20.800 --> 01:10:26.720
[Guest]: permission of her father, her brother, her father-in-law, her husband, and sometimes even the

01:10:26.720 --> 01:10:32.880
[Guest]: entire village panchayat. So I'll give you an example, the hospitality trade. There is a huge

01:10:32.880 --> 01:10:40.000
[Guest]: demand for skilled women. But it is the family that says, but this is not good work for our

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:45.120
[Guest]: daughters. And I've spoken to fathers who have said, my daughter's not going to serve food to men

01:10:45.120 --> 01:10:50.160
[Guest]: in a restaurant. You make her a captain. Now, how can she become a captain unless she's first

01:10:50.160 --> 01:10:57.520
[Guest]: serving? So there is a demand. The jobs are there. But the families say this is not appropriate,

01:10:57.520 --> 01:11:02.560
[Guest]: or the village will say this girl. So there's an institute that's training women for the

01:11:02.560 --> 01:11:11.680
[Guest]: hospitality trade in Aurangabad. This is run by Pratham. And the women who enroll, who get in,

01:11:11.680 --> 01:11:17.840
[Guest]: they actually get their fees subsidized to a very, very large degree compared to men.

01:11:18.800 --> 01:11:24.800
[Guest]: Yet, despite the subsidy, only 30% of its intake is women. And of those 30%,

01:11:24.800 --> 01:11:32.000
[Guest]: 50%, a large proportion who get job offers after they've complete, don't accept their

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:37.520
[Guest]: jobs because the girls are coming from tribal belts, from faraway villages. And the families,

01:11:37.520 --> 01:11:41.760
[Guest]: first of all, don't want to send them even to train. And second of all, when they send them

01:11:41.760 --> 01:11:46.960
[Guest]: to train, don't want them to live that far away. So they're allowed to come in batches. If they

01:11:46.960 --> 01:11:50.400
[Guest]: come with three, four, five from the same village, they send them. But then three,

01:11:50.400 --> 01:11:55.520
[Guest]: four, five cannot get a job in the same place. They have to be separated. And once girls are

01:11:55.520 --> 01:12:01.440
[Guest]: separated, the parents don't want to send them off. And I'll never forget this one man I met.

01:12:01.440 --> 01:12:06.800
[Guest]: He was so angry. He was a truck driver and his daughter had done the course and she had actually

01:12:06.800 --> 01:12:10.800
[Guest]: joined it while he was off traveling somewhere, driving his truck. And when he came back,

01:12:10.800 --> 01:12:15.680
[Guest]: he discovered that she had joined this hospitality course. And he was very angry because he had not

01:12:15.680 --> 01:12:21.840
[Guest]: been consulted. And he just went on and I said, but what's wrong? Why? She had a job offer.

01:12:21.840 --> 01:12:27.760
[Guest]: So he's, he's the one who told me, and she should not serve food. And he had all these objections.

01:12:27.760 --> 01:12:33.840
[Guest]: And finally, in the end, he tells me, he says, I know what happens when girls get jobs. I said,

01:12:33.840 --> 01:12:39.040
[Guest]: what? So he says, they do love marriages. You know, so the authority of the patriarch could

01:12:39.040 --> 01:12:44.480
[Guest]: get eroded. And he gave me the example of his niece who had joined the police. And he says,

01:12:44.480 --> 01:12:48.640
[Guest]: you know, she joined the police and then she did a court marriage. And now her father is so

01:12:48.640 --> 01:12:54.640
[Guest]: embarrassed. He cannot show his face anywhere. So this is the mindset you are encountering in

01:12:54.640 --> 01:13:00.480
[Guest]: larger and lesser degrees. And, and so that is why I say it's the families can be supportive.

01:13:00.480 --> 01:13:05.360
[Guest]: I mean, if families choose, well, I'll give you an example. When we spoke about the motherhood

01:13:05.360 --> 01:13:11.200
[Guest]: penalty, there is data that suggests that in families where there is a mother-in-law,

01:13:11.200 --> 01:13:16.800
[Guest]: women are more likely to work because they will look after the children. They will take a lot of

01:13:16.800 --> 01:13:21.920
[Guest]: the burden of the cooking and of a lot of the other work. So mother-in-laws can be extremely

01:13:21.920 --> 01:13:27.760
[Guest]: supportive of women when they choose to be. This is the saas bahu serial no one has ever seen.

01:13:27.760 --> 01:13:33.200
[Amit Varma]: Yes. And, and, and, you know, the, the interesting thing also is that even if jobs are available,

01:13:33.200 --> 01:13:38.000
[Amit Varma]: even if women want to do them, even if their families just imagine are happy with them doing

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:43.120
[Amit Varma]: the jobs, sometimes they can't because of external circumstances. And coming back to Haryana,

01:13:43.120 --> 01:13:47.760
[Amit Varma]: you've written a piece where the headline of the piece says it all, which is how rapes are

01:13:47.760 --> 01:13:53.840
[Amit Varma]: impacting the mobility of women. And you point out in the piece that number one, sometimes a job

01:13:53.840 --> 01:13:58.560
[Amit Varma]: involves even a little bit of travel. And, you know, that is dangerous to women because there

01:13:58.560 --> 01:14:05.040
[Amit Varma]: is simply no rule of law anywhere in this country, let alone Haryana. And secondly, you quote the

01:14:05.040 --> 01:14:10.000
[Amit Varma]: social worker called Kanta Singh, which is quote, when one girl is raped in a village, parents of

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:15.760
[Amit Varma]: the other girls will impose even more restrictions on their movement outside the house. Stop quote.

01:14:15.760 --> 01:14:19.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's actually rational on the part of parents to impose those restrictions.

01:14:19.200 --> 01:14:25.680
[Guest]: Absolutely. Kanta, of course, is a wonderful woman. She's with UNDP, very, she's from Haryana

01:14:25.680 --> 01:14:32.960
[Guest]: and a sports woman, very passionate about bringing skilling to women in, in Haryana.

01:14:32.960 --> 01:14:39.200
[Guest]: So let me give you an example. UNDP did a skilling program for the textile trade. And these,

01:14:39.920 --> 01:14:46.320
[Guest]: I forget now how many women, 50 or 60 of them were trained and were placed in jobs and went off

01:14:46.320 --> 01:14:54.000
[Guest]: to work. Within a month, there was only one woman left. Those 59 out of 60 had just dropped out

01:14:54.560 --> 01:14:59.680
[Guest]: because it was too far, the bus was taking too long. And so I tracked down one of them,

01:14:59.680 --> 01:15:04.720
[Guest]: you know, that was a job. I tracked down one of them and I sat down with her and she explained

01:15:04.720 --> 01:15:12.880
[Guest]: to me, she said, when I did this skilling program, it was the summer. The days are long. Okay. And I

01:15:12.880 --> 01:15:18.320
[Guest]: took this job and it was a one month skilling program and this job was great. It was dropping.

01:15:18.320 --> 01:15:24.320
[Guest]: But she says in the winter, when the days became shorter, she says, my bus stop is one kilometer

01:15:24.320 --> 01:15:32.880
[Guest]: from my village. I have to walk home in the dark. So forget Haryana, all over India, you know,

01:15:32.880 --> 01:15:38.400
[Guest]: including in Delhi and Bombay, the big metros, the average, national average of women who use

01:15:38.400 --> 01:15:48.400
[Guest]: public transport for work is what? Take a guess. I won't even take a guess. 22%. Only 22% women

01:15:48.400 --> 01:15:55.200
[Guest]: women take public transport to work. There are many inhibiting factors. One is they don't want

01:15:55.200 --> 01:16:01.520
[Guest]: to spend too much time, right? Because they have other things to do back at home. So if you go to

01:16:01.520 --> 01:16:08.320
[Guest]: Bawana, which is on the outskirts of Delhi, women are bringing home job work from the nearby

01:16:08.320 --> 01:16:16.480
[Guest]: factories, you know, for pathetic wages, you know, well below minimum standards, 100 rupees a day for

01:16:16.480 --> 01:16:21.760
[Guest]: packing a garbatti, you know, which is back, you know, it's mind numbing work or bringing home

01:16:22.480 --> 01:16:27.120
[Guest]: fan components, which then the whole family sits together, children, everybody sit together and

01:16:27.120 --> 01:16:33.280
[Guest]: they help the mom out. She's getting 5,500 because she can't afford to go to work.

01:16:33.840 --> 01:16:39.600
[Guest]: She cannot afford it either in terms of time or in terms of money. You know, a metro ticket is an

01:16:39.600 --> 01:16:44.960
[Guest]: expensive thing for a woman. So she will get a much better paying job. So when a resettlement

01:16:44.960 --> 01:16:50.000
[Guest]: colony like Bawana comes up, because the Supreme Court says polluting industries must be moved out

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:55.120
[Guest]: from, how does it impact the lives of women? This is how it impacts the lives of women,

01:16:55.120 --> 01:16:58.640
[Guest]: that they can no longer, they have to give up jobs, which they might have had,

01:16:59.360 --> 01:17:04.000
[Guest]: paying them better because they were in the heart of the city. They've now been thrown into some

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:09.600
[Guest]: wild wilderness where there is an extremely high crime rate. So there are mothers I spoke to who

01:17:09.600 --> 01:17:13.680
[Guest]: said, I can't go to work for eight hours because when I come back, I don't know if my kid is going

01:17:13.680 --> 01:17:18.640
[Guest]: to be here or not. My kid could be snatched. My daughter could be, you know, whatever, disappeared.

01:17:19.200 --> 01:17:25.520
[Guest]: It happens. They have an enormously high crime rate. So crime does impact women's workforce

01:17:25.520 --> 01:17:29.680
[Guest]: participation, both in terms of their own participation and in terms of the mothers,

01:17:29.680 --> 01:17:34.800
[Guest]: because then the mothers are now doing chowkidari. So this one woman who does this agarbatti packing

01:17:34.800 --> 01:17:39.360
[Guest]: business, she told me, she said, when my daughter gets married, I'll look for a full-time job.

01:17:39.360 --> 01:17:45.520
[Guest]: But till she's married, I have to do her hifazat. This kind of brings me to a point I often make

01:17:45.520 --> 01:17:50.720
[Amit Varma]: about the Indian state, that in my view, the Indian state should be a small but strong state,

01:17:50.720 --> 01:17:54.640
[Amit Varma]: while right now it's broad and weak. Like there are a few things that the state should do,

01:17:54.640 --> 01:17:58.960
[Amit Varma]: and it should focus on doing them well. And one of them is a rule of law. So, you know,

01:17:58.960 --> 01:18:03.840
[Amit Varma]: there is all this conversation about, we should make this policy intervention or that policy

01:18:03.840 --> 01:18:09.360
[Amit Varma]: intervention to help women out. But the basic fact is that if you just have the rule of law,

01:18:09.360 --> 01:18:14.960
[Amit Varma]: if you just do that bit properly, so many of these problems can be, you know,

01:18:14.960 --> 01:18:19.920
[Guest]: not solved, but so much better. Absolutely. There's no question. There's no question.

01:18:19.920 --> 01:18:24.880
[Guest]: You know, recently, for instance, the UP government made an announcement saying that

01:18:24.880 --> 01:18:31.760
[Guest]: they will provide free travel to women on the metros and on the buses. And of course, I mean,

01:18:31.760 --> 01:18:38.240
[Guest]: I wrote a piece for Economic Times saying that it's a great move. But the caveat, which is,

01:18:38.240 --> 01:18:45.440
[Guest]: you need to consider the costs. You need to, please don't do something that sounds populist.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:51.360
[Guest]: You know, what is the nitty gritty? So, you bring in a policy intervention, but how are you going

01:18:51.360 --> 01:18:58.960
[Guest]: to implement this policy? Have you done a cost analysis on increasing public transport vis-a-vis

01:18:58.960 --> 01:19:04.320
[Guest]: the cost of subsidising those tickets? You could just put more buses on the road. Bawana, for

01:19:04.320 --> 01:19:09.920
[Guest]: instance, does not even have public transport. So, how does it help that poor Agarbati Packer,

01:19:09.920 --> 01:19:13.760
[Guest]: who is waiting for her daughter to get married so she can get back into the workforce? It doesn't

01:19:13.760 --> 01:19:19.200
[Guest]: help her because there is no bus. There is no metro. She walks to work. Well, she actually

01:19:19.200 --> 01:19:23.520
[Guest]: works from house, but her neighbours, for instance, those who do work, they either walk to work or

01:19:23.520 --> 01:19:27.840
[Guest]: they take those shared auto rickshaws, which, you know, five rupees a head or something.

01:19:27.840 --> 01:19:32.640
[Guest]: So, this subsidy is not going to help them. So, what is the implementation of the policy?

01:19:33.280 --> 01:19:37.680
[Guest]: That is what worries me. You know, we kind of make these wonderful announcements and then we

01:19:37.680 --> 01:19:44.160
[Amit Varma]: don't think about how we're going to follow through. Let's kind of move on now to an issue,

01:19:44.160 --> 01:19:49.440
[Amit Varma]: which I guess doesn't impact most women in India, but does impact those of us in the elites,

01:19:49.440 --> 01:19:54.400
[Amit Varma]: which is the whole Me Too movement. What was your sense of it? Well, it does impact most women

01:19:54.400 --> 01:19:58.080
[Amit Varma]: in India. In the sense, it's an issue for most women, but most women in India probably are not

01:19:58.080 --> 01:20:01.680
[Guest]: even aware that there was something like that. Well, most women in India, I would imagine,

01:20:01.680 --> 01:20:08.560
[Guest]: at the workplace experience it in some form or the other. The 96% who are in the informal sector

01:20:08.560 --> 01:20:14.720
[Guest]: do have a protection in law, which is in paper, because you're not going to, you know, speak up

01:20:14.720 --> 01:20:19.280
[Guest]: and you don't, you have these two district committees in Delhi, all of Delhi. So, which

01:20:19.280 --> 01:20:23.920
[Guest]: domestic worker is going to complain because, you know, her boss is watching porn in her presence

01:20:23.920 --> 01:20:28.880
[Guest]: and this happens very often, I'm told, or he'll come out in his towel or maybe not even that.

01:20:28.880 --> 01:20:33.920
[Guest]: I mean, that is sexual harassment. It fits the legal definition of workplace sexual harassment.

01:20:33.920 --> 01:20:40.320
[Guest]: So, she's doing the pocha and the sahab is coming out naked from his shower. She'd just rather quit

01:20:40.320 --> 01:20:45.360
[Guest]: her job and find something else. She's not going to go looking for where she can make this complaint

01:20:45.360 --> 01:20:50.960
[Guest]: right on sexual harassment, which can't even be proved. There is no evidence. But the Me Too

01:20:50.960 --> 01:20:55.360
[Guest]: movement, let us, okay, let's go back to the Me Too movement. I mean, just to clarify, I did not

01:20:55.360 --> 01:21:00.480
[Amit Varma]: for a moment mean that women don't face harassment. It's absolutely ubiquitous. Yeah. But just in

01:21:00.480 --> 01:21:07.840
[Amit Varma]: terms of, you know, what the Me Too movement kind of focused on, I mean, everyone coming out, I mean,

01:21:07.840 --> 01:21:13.440
[Amit Varma]: it's all English speaking elites, unfortunately. It is. And again, back to the point that just

01:21:13.440 --> 01:21:20.000
[Guest]: because you're elite does not mean you do not suffer. Exactly. Right. So, again, let's go back

01:21:20.000 --> 01:21:28.400
[Guest]: to my point about the generational change. I did encounter a predatory boss very early in my career,

01:21:28.400 --> 01:21:34.160
[Guest]: fortunately, and very quickly into my job. I mean, I had not even worked for one month

01:21:34.880 --> 01:21:42.240
[Guest]: when this happened. The incident itself did not upset me. Honestly, it happened in a car. And

01:21:43.680 --> 01:21:47.520
[Guest]: I mean, he was just ridiculous. I was able to push him off. It didn't bother me. I said,

01:21:47.520 --> 01:21:52.880
[Guest]: okay, forget it. But a few days later, because I did tell a few friends about it,

01:21:52.880 --> 01:21:57.920
[Guest]: and a few days later, he summoned me to his office, and I got the dressing down of my life.

01:21:58.640 --> 01:22:02.640
[Guest]: He said, why are you talking about it? Because people will think you're showing off.

01:22:02.640 --> 01:22:09.040
[Guest]: And really, for me, that was the intimidation, the malified, because he knew he had done something

01:22:09.040 --> 01:22:14.000
[Guest]: wrong, right? And the attempt to silence me and throttle me, I said, I'm out of here, man. This

01:22:14.000 --> 01:22:19.520
[Guest]: is just too much. So I served out my three-month notice, partly because it never occurred to me

01:22:19.520 --> 01:22:25.600
[Guest]: that I could ask for a waiver. We started work at a time when there was no term called sexual

01:22:25.600 --> 01:22:31.280
[Guest]: harassment. There was no law. There was no vishaka. There was none of that. So we have a

01:22:31.280 --> 01:22:36.400
[Guest]: little sisterhood where we tell each other, he's a creep. Don't go to his office. He drinks at

01:22:36.400 --> 01:22:43.920
[Guest]: night. Don't go into his cabin. So we looked out for each other, but it was a hazard of the

01:22:43.920 --> 01:22:49.760
[Guest]: job that all of us encountered at some point or the other. I do not know a single woman,

01:22:50.640 --> 01:22:56.480
[Guest]: and you're welcome to ask your female colleagues who have not experienced, at least of my

01:22:56.480 --> 01:23:02.560
[Guest]: generation, who did not experience some form of absolutely blatant sexual harassment. I'm not

01:23:02.560 --> 01:23:08.480
[Guest]: even talking about what the law supposedly protects you against, which includes sexist remarks,

01:23:08.480 --> 01:23:14.160
[Guest]: making off-color jokes in the presence of... I'm not even... That was all the time. All the time.

01:23:14.160 --> 01:23:18.480
[Guest]: You were in the conference room. Your boss would turn to you and say, would you order the coffee?

01:23:18.480 --> 01:23:26.720
[Guest]: Why? Do I have some special coffee-making or coffee-ordering skills? Just because I'm...

01:23:26.720 --> 01:23:32.800
[Guest]: Will you take the notes? Again, why? Because I'm the only woman who's sitting around the table.

01:23:32.800 --> 01:23:40.160
[Guest]: So we forget in the Me Too, it is such a struggle for women to get a seat on the table.

01:23:40.800 --> 01:23:45.440
[Guest]: And I'll tell you a story, Amit. And I read this in the Washington Post some years ago during the

01:23:45.440 --> 01:23:53.360
[Guest]: Obama administration. And Obama was this great, empowered feminist. He was openly a feminist

01:23:53.360 --> 01:23:59.600
[Guest]: leader and he hired a lot of women, but the women were still in a minority in the White House. And

01:23:59.600 --> 01:24:04.560
[Guest]: so what would happen during meetings? And when I tell this story to women, they all understand.

01:24:04.560 --> 01:24:08.720
[Guest]: Their eyes light up because they know exactly what I'm talking about. So you're sitting around

01:24:08.720 --> 01:24:15.120
[Guest]: the conference table. You're maybe 10, 11 women and maybe 20 men. So you're kind of... You're

01:24:15.120 --> 01:24:21.200
[Guest]: there, but you're not in equal numbers. The woman makes a point. The men will look into the air,

01:24:21.200 --> 01:24:27.600
[Guest]: they'll drink their coffee, they'll stare at their phones or whatever. And some man will

01:24:27.600 --> 01:24:34.400
[Guest]: then interrupt and take over. And then five minutes later, a man makes exactly the same point.

01:24:35.200 --> 01:24:40.080
[Guest]: And everybody looks at him and they're clapping and they say, genius idea, man, genius.

01:24:41.040 --> 01:24:46.080
[Guest]: So the women cottoned on to this and they decided that they were going to reinforce each other.

01:24:46.800 --> 01:24:52.800
[Guest]: So if we were on the table and I was sitting with my friend and my friend, my female colleague,

01:24:52.800 --> 01:24:56.800
[Guest]: made a point. And then she was, of course, overruled because men don't listen to women.

01:24:56.800 --> 01:25:00.640
[Guest]: They don't know how to listen to women. I would say, no, let's go back to what

01:25:01.360 --> 01:25:08.560
[Guest]: my friend was saying. And so the women decided consciously as a strategy to reinforce each other

01:25:08.560 --> 01:25:13.840
[Guest]: around the conference table. This is the struggle I'm talking about, Amit, the struggle to get a

01:25:13.840 --> 01:25:21.680
[Guest]: seat on the table. It is no man I know understands that fight. The fight, if you look at my story,

01:25:21.680 --> 01:25:27.120
[Guest]: the fight to run away from an arranged marriage, from a claustrophobic arrangement that your

01:25:27.120 --> 01:25:31.520
[Guest]: parents have planned for you, even though parents who love you, who dearly love you.

01:25:33.200 --> 01:25:38.480
[Guest]: I can't say that my mother was a bad mother. She was a great mom and she was a very liberated mom

01:25:38.480 --> 01:25:42.800
[Guest]: for her age and for her time. But her plan was that you will marry a nice man

01:25:43.920 --> 01:25:49.520
[Guest]: and have children and wear nice, elegant saris and have tea parties and whatever.

01:25:49.520 --> 01:25:53.440
[Guest]: And you can have a career, of course, but your family comes first. She was a lawyer

01:25:54.000 --> 01:26:00.560
[Guest]: who quit her practice. She had a practice in Kanpur and she quit her practice even before

01:26:00.560 --> 01:26:05.120
[Guest]: we were born. She got married and said, well, my children will need me someday.

01:26:05.120 --> 01:26:11.920
[Guest]: So she gave it up in anticipation. And somewhere in her head, I think she resented it because she

01:26:11.920 --> 01:26:17.120
[Guest]: said it very often. I had a great career. I had a great job. But yet as a mom,

01:26:17.120 --> 01:26:21.920
[Guest]: she was not able to unlearn what she had learned, that repression where she had to give it up.

01:26:21.920 --> 01:26:26.320
[Guest]: She resented giving it up, but she was not yet free enough to give us the freedom to say,

01:26:26.320 --> 01:26:30.320
[Guest]: go and live your life. Doesn't matter if you're not married. Doesn't matter if you don't live at

01:26:30.320 --> 01:26:35.360
[Guest]: home. Doesn't matter if you don't wear elegant saris and have nice teas. Go and have a job,

01:26:35.360 --> 01:26:38.160
[Guest]: have a career, because if you were my son, I would expect the same from you.

01:26:39.040 --> 01:26:43.040
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that I sort of welcomed about the MeToo movement, and again, when I

01:26:43.040 --> 01:26:48.160
[Amit Varma]: called it elite, I wasn't criticizing it. It was a lament that it should have been more widespread.

01:26:48.160 --> 01:26:53.440
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that I kind of welcomed about it was that a lot of these sexist attitudes,

01:26:53.440 --> 01:26:59.920
[Amit Varma]: which were normalized, were suddenly being condemned very emphatically. For example,

01:26:59.920 --> 01:27:04.160
[Amit Varma]: all of those little things like the off color joke, so you take the note, so you get the water

01:27:04.160 --> 01:27:08.720
[Amit Varma]: and all of these attitudes were considered completely normal, you know, and a lot of women

01:27:08.720 --> 01:27:13.520
[Amit Varma]: a lot of women in an earlier generation might have taken it for granted that there will be predators

01:27:13.520 --> 01:27:18.240
[Amit Varma]: around, just avoid them and be careful. And that's all you need to do about it. And a lot of predators

01:27:18.240 --> 01:27:22.640
[Amit Varma]: might also have taken for granted that no one's going to protest at what we do. And our success

01:27:22.640 --> 01:27:27.440
[Amit Varma]: rate will be good enough to make it rational to continue predating, if I may use that verb.

01:27:27.440 --> 01:27:33.040
[Amit Varma]: And I think to some extent, MeToo changed that understanding, at least in whatever circles it

01:27:33.040 --> 01:27:38.800
[Amit Varma]: was widespread, and changed the incentives for men as well to behave because who knows who will

01:27:38.800 --> 01:27:43.920
[Guest]: get called out next. Absolutely. Listen, in the early days of the, I'm talking about because,

01:27:43.920 --> 01:27:47.600
[Guest]: you know, there are various MeToo movements, you know, are we talking about Bhavri Devi?

01:27:48.160 --> 01:27:52.320
[Guest]: And what happened in Rajasthan? Or are we talking about Raya Sarkar's list,

01:27:52.320 --> 01:27:56.880
[Guest]: which created a huge controversy, even amongst feminists and even amongst women,

01:27:56.880 --> 01:28:02.480
[Guest]: tragically, where you had young feminists and old feminists getting into this needless scuffle,

01:28:02.480 --> 01:28:07.440
[Guest]: because we dissipated our energy. Instead of understanding what is the enemy and who is the

01:28:07.440 --> 01:28:11.120
[Guest]: enemy, we started fighting amongst each other, where the younger feminist said,

01:28:11.120 --> 01:28:15.040
[Guest]: due process doesn't work. And the older feminist said, no, you have to believe in due process.

01:28:15.600 --> 01:28:21.920
[Guest]: And so that debate kind of fizzled out. Then you come to October 2018, where you suddenly have

01:28:21.920 --> 01:28:26.720
[Guest]: one woman, you know, starting with Tanushree Dutta's interview, then you have Bahima Kukreja.

01:28:26.720 --> 01:28:33.280
[Guest]: And remember, these men who are being brought down were so-called woke feminist men,

01:28:33.840 --> 01:28:40.880
[Guest]: who were working in comedy. And so, you know, Utsav Chakraborty set the cat amongst pigeons,

01:28:40.880 --> 01:28:48.640
[Guest]: because he kind of condemned very bad behaviour by men, male employees of a pan masala company,

01:28:48.640 --> 01:28:53.600
[Guest]: who were sent off on a cruise to Australia, behaved very badly as to be expected. And he said,

01:28:53.600 --> 01:28:57.600
[Guest]: look at these men. And Mahima said, you're a hypocrite, because what have you been doing?

01:28:57.600 --> 01:29:02.640
[Guest]: And then she, of course, exposed him. So there was evidence, there were screenshots,

01:29:02.640 --> 01:29:08.480
[Guest]: and the men could not deny it. What was unprecedented was the fact that companies

01:29:08.480 --> 01:29:16.960
[Guest]: took up and took note. You know, so there was a very big piya kulpa, where AIB, for instance,

01:29:16.960 --> 01:29:24.400
[Guest]: just was disbanded. Phantom Films was disbanded. I know of media companies where they said,

01:29:24.400 --> 01:29:31.600
[Guest]: even though the complainant had moved on to another job, they said, no, we'll hold an inquiry.

01:29:31.600 --> 01:29:36.320
[Guest]: And then there were sensitization trainings. And I know at one of the sensitization trainings

01:29:36.320 --> 01:29:43.120
[Guest]: that was conducted by my friend Paromita Vora of Agents of Ishq, where a woman put up her hand,

01:29:43.120 --> 01:29:47.680
[Guest]: and she said, I want to say something. So she said, bolo. So she says, you know, when I'm making

01:29:47.680 --> 01:29:53.120
[Guest]: the pages, my boss stands very close to me, and I don't like it. It's uncomfortable. And none of the

01:29:53.120 --> 01:29:57.440
[Guest]: men had ever thought of that, because when you're making the pages, you will stand over someone's

01:29:57.440 --> 01:30:02.640
[Guest]: shoulder. So she said, okay, let's do an exercise. What is a comfortable distance? And so they

01:30:02.640 --> 01:30:07.760
[Guest]: actually did it. So this woman stood there and she said, well, I'm comfortable if you're standing

01:30:07.760 --> 01:30:14.800
[Guest]: here. But if you come any closer, it really makes me very uncomfortable. So the men had not realized

01:30:14.800 --> 01:30:21.440
[Guest]: this. They were not being creepy. They just hadn't realized. They hadn't understood that.

01:30:22.560 --> 01:30:28.560
[Guest]: Of course, the first days were very exhilarating. You know, it was happening so fast. It was

01:30:28.560 --> 01:30:34.480
[Guest]: organic. These were women coming forward. And you know, I mean, for women like me, my God,

01:30:34.480 --> 01:30:40.160
[Guest]: I mean, this is a whole, it was a revelation that here you have this generation of strong,

01:30:40.800 --> 01:30:44.960
[Guest]: and again, we're talking about a very small minority. We're not, we don't have to add that

01:30:44.960 --> 01:30:50.640
[Guest]: caveat every time we're talking about the Me Too movement. But these were like strong, assertive

01:30:50.640 --> 01:30:55.920
[Guest]: women who said, I'm not going to be silent. You know, I'm not going to make the compromises you

01:30:55.920 --> 01:30:59.920
[Guest]: guys made. You know, you guys may have been brought up to say, well, compromise, learn the

01:30:59.920 --> 01:31:04.560
[Guest]: tricks of the trade. How do you get along? Predator boss, avoid him, blah, blah, blah. We're not going

01:31:04.560 --> 01:31:08.800
[Guest]: to do that because we have rights at work and we will voice those rights. And they had evidence in

01:31:08.800 --> 01:31:15.200
[Guest]: terms of screenshots. They had initially at least the support of companies. But a year later,

01:31:15.200 --> 01:31:21.520
[Guest]: what happened? You know, it's a sad story. If you look at so many of the early cases,

01:31:22.400 --> 01:31:29.200
[Guest]: whether it is R. K. Pachori at Terry, six years after this woman spoke up and made a complaint,

01:31:29.200 --> 01:31:34.080
[Guest]: both to her ICC, as well as to the police station, the trial is limping along.

01:31:34.640 --> 01:31:40.320
[Guest]: Tarun Tejpal, Tehelka, what happened? Trial is limping along. You know, so

01:31:41.760 --> 01:31:45.200
[Guest]: these are, of course, the older cases, but coming even to the Me Too cases,

01:31:45.760 --> 01:31:49.600
[Guest]: very quickly, there was a fight back. There's always a pushback, right, for men.

01:31:50.400 --> 01:31:56.080
[Guest]: So the criminal defamation, that's why the M. G. Akbar case is so interesting. It is not M. G.

01:31:56.080 --> 01:32:01.440
[Guest]: Akbar who's on trial. Please remember, M. G. Akbar has been accused by 20 women,

01:32:01.440 --> 01:32:06.640
[Guest]: including by one woman of rape. Okay, what she has said is that it was rape.

01:32:08.000 --> 01:32:14.240
[Guest]: He is not under trial. He has filed a criminal defamation against one of his early tweeters,

01:32:14.240 --> 01:32:20.080
[Guest]: Priya Ramani, who actually says he didn't do anything. And this trial is still going on

01:32:20.080 --> 01:32:25.120
[Guest]: in court and I'm watching which way it will go. Not just because Priya Ramani is my friend,

01:32:25.120 --> 01:32:32.800
[Guest]: but also because I really believe in this. I really believe, I want us as a society to ask,

01:32:32.800 --> 01:32:38.560
[Guest]: to look into our own hearts and say, what will it take for women to speak up against injustice?

01:32:39.360 --> 01:32:43.600
[Amit Varma]: And that was kind of one of the, like, again, when Me Too happened last year,

01:32:43.600 --> 01:32:47.360
[Amit Varma]: more so than Me Too and Raya Sarkar's list, but when it happened last year,

01:32:47.360 --> 01:32:51.600
[Amit Varma]: that was one of the things that gave me hope that number one, so many women are speaking out.

01:32:51.600 --> 01:32:56.400
[Amit Varma]: And number two, this now changes the incentives for both men and women. Women are more likely to

01:32:56.400 --> 01:33:02.640
[Amit Varma]: speak out and articulate their grievances. And men are more likely to be careful of their behavior,

01:33:02.640 --> 01:33:08.240
[Amit Varma]: even if that is a wrong reason to behave well, it is at least a start. And I'm not so sure now,

01:33:08.240 --> 01:33:11.920
[Amit Varma]: a few months on whether my optimism was misplaced or justified.

01:33:11.920 --> 01:33:17.200
[Guest]: Yeah, well, I was also optimistic. I was like, wow, new deal for women. And one year later,

01:33:17.200 --> 01:33:24.080
[Guest]: where are we? You know, Alok Nath, a case against him has been dismissed. Ajay Devgn says,

01:33:24.880 --> 01:33:29.040
[Guest]: somebody who was accused of sexual harassment, he said, I believe in the Me Too movement.

01:33:29.040 --> 01:33:33.840
[Guest]: You know, I really believe in this movement, but however, I can't reshoot portions of it,

01:33:33.840 --> 01:33:39.680
[Guest]: because there'll be a very big cost involved. Writers who have been named, have publishing

01:33:39.680 --> 01:33:47.120
[Guest]: books with publishers. M.J. Akbar is writing columns, for God's sake. M.J. Akbar has a cover

01:33:47.120 --> 01:33:52.560
[Guest]: story coming out in Open Magazine. Now, I'm not saying that these guys should be, you know,

01:33:52.560 --> 01:33:59.280
[Guest]: sent into Kalapani, but at least while the case is on, let us hear and what are we as a society.

01:33:59.280 --> 01:34:04.240
[Guest]: So this is the same story, Amit, whether it is sexual harassment at the workplace or domestic

01:34:04.240 --> 01:34:10.240
[Guest]: violence. I'm coming back to that figure of one in three women. One in three women have been beaten.

01:34:10.800 --> 01:34:15.600
[Guest]: We know who these women are. They are our neighbors. We hear the screams at night. They

01:34:15.600 --> 01:34:20.960
[Guest]: come to us in the morning with bruises and bandages. We give them a cup of tea, we hug

01:34:20.960 --> 01:34:27.920
[Guest]: them and we send them right back. So what is happening is the same story. The cost of speaking

01:34:27.920 --> 01:34:34.400
[Guest]: up is just too high for any kind of violence, whether it is domestic violence, sexual harassment,

01:34:34.400 --> 01:34:39.280
[Guest]: rape. The spotlight is on the women. Who's on trial? M.J. Akbar is not on trial. Priya Ramani

01:34:39.280 --> 01:34:47.680
[Guest]: is on trial. If convicted, she will go to jail for two years. So hand on heart, you know,

01:34:47.680 --> 01:34:54.720
[Amit Varma]: what are we talking about? Yeah. And she's an absolute hero. I'll ask you a bunch of general

01:34:54.720 --> 01:34:58.800
[Amit Varma]: questions that I had kind of saved for the end because I've taken up a lot of your time and this

01:34:58.800 --> 01:35:06.320
[Amit Varma]: is not at all. It's been a pleasure. This is unpaid work for you. But good unpaid work. Yeah.

01:35:06.320 --> 01:35:12.640
[Amit Varma]: Okay. So question number one. And this is something that always kind of strikes me is that

01:35:12.640 --> 01:35:17.840
[Amit Varma]: at the end of the day, women are almost 50 percent of the vote bank, slightly less than 50 percent

01:35:17.840 --> 01:35:22.320
[Amit Varma]: because 919 women for every thousand men. But they're almost 50 percent of the vote bank. And

01:35:22.320 --> 01:35:28.160
[Amit Varma]: you'd imagine that any political party, which positions itself as woman friendly in a genuine

01:35:28.160 --> 01:35:33.520
[Amit Varma]: way beyond mere posturing, can actually get a significant vote bank on a side. And yet this

01:35:33.520 --> 01:35:37.920
[Amit Varma]: does not happen. Women tend to follow the same kind of positions as the men in their families

01:35:37.920 --> 01:35:44.560
[Guest]: do. Why is this? Yes and no. I don't think women often follow the same position as their husbands,

01:35:45.200 --> 01:35:50.720
[Guest]: though husbands may like to believe that. And women are smart. Women are not stupid. So I'm

01:35:50.720 --> 01:35:55.280
[Guest]: not sure that they always follow the family dictate. But women also remember one thing. We

01:35:55.280 --> 01:36:01.200
[Guest]: don't vote as a vote bank. We don't vote as a bloc. You know, I mean, there is some evidence

01:36:01.200 --> 01:36:05.200
[Guest]: that in the last and I think that evidence is still being passed. So I don't want to comment

01:36:05.200 --> 01:36:10.720
[Guest]: too much on it. That women tend to go more with the Congress than with the BJP. But let's look

01:36:10.720 --> 01:36:15.440
[Guest]: at evidence. Let's wait for the evidence. How many Muslim women, for instance, did any Muslim women

01:36:15.440 --> 01:36:21.120
[Guest]: vote for the BJP because of triple talaq? We don't know. What was the impact of the Give Up Your

01:36:21.120 --> 01:36:26.800
[Guest]: Subsidy or of Swachh Bharat on the women vote? You know, these are interesting questions. But

01:36:26.800 --> 01:36:33.280
[Guest]: very interestingly, I'll tell you, states that do very well on gender indices, you think of Kerala,

01:36:33.280 --> 01:36:38.240
[Guest]: you think of the Northeast, which otherwise, you know, Meghalaya, for instance, has a workforce

01:36:38.240 --> 01:36:44.880
[Guest]: participation of almost 36%. But they have never elected, you know, a lot of the Northeast states

01:36:44.880 --> 01:36:53.120
[Guest]: have never seen a woman contestant, let alone a woman MP. Manipur is one of them. And so while

01:36:53.120 --> 01:36:59.040
[Guest]: at Kerala, very few women go into parliament or to the assemblies, whereas states like Haryana,

01:36:59.040 --> 01:37:05.280
[Guest]: Punjab and Shamika Ravi of Brookings has studied that at great length, saying that women don't

01:37:05.280 --> 01:37:09.600
[Guest]: necessarily want to vote for women. You know, they want to vote for someone who they feel will

01:37:09.600 --> 01:37:16.720
[Guest]: be on their side. Naveen Patnaik, I mean, when history is written, I think there's this very

01:37:16.720 --> 01:37:25.280
[Guest]: special thank you note due to him for taking the risk in actually saying that 33% seats in

01:37:25.280 --> 01:37:30.000
[Guest]: parliament, not in the assemblies yet, will be reserved for women. And so who do you have? Yes,

01:37:30.000 --> 01:37:37.360
[Guest]: you have the Bahubeti category. And I'm actually genuinely amused when people say, oh, if you have

01:37:37.360 --> 01:37:42.240
[Guest]: reservation for women, they will all come in the Bahubeti category, because of course, the beta,

01:37:43.040 --> 01:37:47.520
[Guest]: bhatija category doesn't upset anyone. You understand? So men who are coming, the young

01:37:47.520 --> 01:37:52.480
[Guest]: MPs who are coming in, yeah, that doesn't upset anyone. But when a woman, my God, then you suddenly

01:37:52.480 --> 01:37:58.000
[Guest]: say, oh, but she's the daughter, she's the daughter-in-law. And I'm sorry, I've just lost

01:37:58.000 --> 01:38:03.840
[Amit Varma]: my train of thought. No, no, this was pretty much what I was asking that. I mean, I know women don't

01:38:03.840 --> 01:38:08.320
[Amit Varma]: vote as a bloc and no one should vote as a bloc. You should make your individual judgments. But at

01:38:08.320 --> 01:38:13.920
[Amit Varma]: the same time, you would imagine that women can actually form a very large interest group when

01:38:13.920 --> 01:38:18.320
[Amit Varma]: it comes to their interests, and yet they do not do so. And perhaps that's because of the ingrained

01:38:18.320 --> 01:38:23.840
[Guest]: patriarchy, which many women also represent, I guess. Yeah, and I think also in a lot of elections,

01:38:23.840 --> 01:38:29.760
[Guest]: sometimes you just want to vote. So when a party is headed by a woman, for instance, Mamata,

01:38:29.760 --> 01:38:35.760
[Guest]: who actually brought in even more women than Naveen Patnaik, many of whom are making headlines

01:38:35.760 --> 01:38:41.520
[Guest]: like Mahua Moitra. They're just coming in, they're assertive. There's a new kind of woman.

01:38:41.520 --> 01:38:47.520
[Guest]: So it is changing, but it's not changing fast enough. So we are congratulating ourselves

01:38:47.520 --> 01:38:55.280
[Guest]: because we're now no longer 12.6% representation in parliament. We're wow, we're 14%. So there is

01:38:55.280 --> 01:39:00.960
[Guest]: one school of thought that says, let's forget about hammering on and on about 33% reservation.

01:39:00.960 --> 01:39:07.040
[Guest]: It's not happened in 25 years. It's not going to happen. Why don't we look at increasing the

01:39:07.040 --> 01:39:12.960
[Guest]: number of parliamentary seats? Our population is now 1.3 billion. So there has to be, let's do a

01:39:12.960 --> 01:39:19.920
[Guest]: study and find out that, I mean, how many people is an MP supposed to represent? The IITs did it.

01:39:19.920 --> 01:39:25.920
[Guest]: You remember the IIT said, then we're not going to have reservation in the existing seats for women,

01:39:25.920 --> 01:39:30.960
[Guest]: but because we want more women to come into the IITs, we'll increase the number of seats. So

01:39:30.960 --> 01:39:34.640
[Guest]: increase the number of seats in parliament and give it for women. So you're not taking away

01:39:34.640 --> 01:39:40.000
[Guest]: what is perceived to be a man's seat. It's a political hot potato though,

01:39:40.000 --> 01:39:43.440
[Amit Varma]: because if you look at MP per number of constituents, what's happened over the

01:39:43.440 --> 01:39:48.400
[Amit Varma]: last few decades is that the number of constituents per MP has gone up massively

01:39:48.400 --> 01:39:53.200
[Amit Varma]: in the North and not so much in the South. So if you were to normalize that, you would suddenly have

01:39:53.200 --> 01:39:58.000
[Amit Varma]: many more MPs from the cow belt, so to say, which is far more mythogenistic anywhere.

01:39:58.000 --> 01:40:01.280
[Amit Varma]: They're thereby punishing the South for no fault of their own.

01:40:02.160 --> 01:40:07.360
[Guest]: There are no easy solutions or answers. You're right Amit, I mean, there is no easy solution.

01:40:08.800 --> 01:40:14.720
[Amit Varma]: Another question, which is that over the 30 years that you've been in journalism, and I did an

01:40:14.720 --> 01:40:19.920
[Amit Varma]: episode on the metrics for women's empowerment, which was a fun episode with three ladies,

01:40:19.920 --> 01:40:25.680
[Amit Varma]: Devika Kher, Nidhi Gupta and Hamsini Hariharan, which was about what kind of interesting metrics

01:40:25.680 --> 01:40:32.080
[Amit Varma]: can we use to see whether women are getting empowered or not. And some were conventional,

01:40:32.080 --> 01:40:37.280
[Amit Varma]: some were unconventional. But over the 30 years that you've sort of been a journalist and tracking

01:40:37.280 --> 01:40:43.440
[Amit Varma]: these issues and so on, what are the kind of metrics you can offhand think of, which immediately

01:40:43.440 --> 01:40:47.280
[Amit Varma]: make you think that, okay, this indicates that women are doing better?

01:40:47.280 --> 01:40:53.520
[Guest]: So I'll point you to a study done recently by Nandi Foundation called Teenage Aspirations of

01:40:53.520 --> 01:41:00.560
[Guest]: Girls, TAG, they've called it TAG. And it's a survey of, I believe, 70,000 girls, teenage girls

01:41:00.560 --> 01:41:08.240
[Guest]: across India, rural, urban, small town, big town, etc, etc. And some of the metrics they've used,

01:41:08.240 --> 01:41:13.920
[Guest]: because this is an aspirational survey, and the metrics that they've used is dreaming. How do you

01:41:13.920 --> 01:41:21.920
[Guest]: dream? What do you want, desire? And 70% of these young teenage girls said they want careers before

01:41:21.920 --> 01:41:27.360
[Guest]: marriage. That is heartening. Whether it actually happens in their life or not, I don't know, but

01:41:27.360 --> 01:41:32.880
[Guest]: it is heartening that these girls, so that is an unusual metric to take. We're done with the

01:41:32.880 --> 01:41:38.400
[Guest]: literacy, maternal mortality, infant mortality, blah, blah. The conventional metrics must remain.

01:41:38.400 --> 01:41:44.480
[Guest]: But equally, I would like to say that I am worried that some of the conventional data is no longer

01:41:44.480 --> 01:41:50.240
[Guest]: available to us. And it's not just jobs. For instance, National Crime Records Bureau has not

01:41:50.240 --> 01:41:56.000
[Guest]: been updated for the last two years. That is worrying. So how are we tracking crimes against

01:41:56.000 --> 01:42:02.320
[Guest]: women? Also, when you look at some crimes against women, for example, rape, let's take one example

01:42:02.320 --> 01:42:09.520
[Guest]: of rape. I don't know the answer to the question of whether the actual number of rape cases are

01:42:09.520 --> 01:42:14.800
[Guest]: going up or whether reporting has increased. If it is reporting that has increased, it's a good

01:42:14.800 --> 01:42:20.480
[Guest]: thing. That means women are confident of a system, they're more assertive, they believe they will get

01:42:20.480 --> 01:42:26.720
[Guest]: justice. This is a generation of women who will not be silenced. If it's the number of cases that

01:42:26.720 --> 01:42:32.320
[Guest]: are going up, then that is more worrying. The NCRB, of course, does not distinguish and does not give

01:42:32.320 --> 01:42:36.720
[Guest]: us the answer to that question. And in fact, does not answer the question at all, because we haven't

01:42:36.720 --> 01:42:41.600
[Amit Varma]: had the data updated for two years. In fact, you know, going back to the earlier discussion

01:42:41.600 --> 01:42:46.640
[Amit Varma]: we were having on family values, I once wrote a column for which I got roundly trolled, which

01:42:46.640 --> 01:42:51.760
[Amit Varma]: essentially argued that one of the best metrics for women's empowerment is the rising divorce

01:42:51.760 --> 01:42:55.840
[Guest]: rates. And that is a damn good thing, because it means more women are being able to leave bad

01:42:55.840 --> 01:43:06.160
[Guest]: marriages. Yes, absolutely. I would agree. I'm not a great fan of family as it exists. I see how it

01:43:06.160 --> 01:43:14.560
[Guest]: can be wonderful. And I remember I was at a dinner where this man, who's a very good friend of mine,

01:43:14.560 --> 01:43:19.280
[Guest]: actually, was talking about the great glories of the joint family. And I asked him, I said,

01:43:19.280 --> 01:43:26.080
[Guest]: why don't you ask your wife what she thinks? Because this joint family is sold. And what

01:43:26.080 --> 01:43:32.000
[Guest]: about women and their freedom, their assertion, their desire? Because a joint family will cater

01:43:32.000 --> 01:43:36.400
[Guest]: to the lowest common denominator. The great thing about a joint family is that it takes care of

01:43:36.400 --> 01:43:43.360
[Guest]: everybody. Nobody is left out of the net. But the not so great thing is that it enforces a certain

01:43:43.360 --> 01:43:48.800
[Guest]: rule, a family rule that then becomes invalid. So women chafe at it.

01:43:50.160 --> 01:43:56.240
[Amit Varma]: Right. In terms of public policy, and I'll kind of elaborate on what I mean by this question.

01:43:56.240 --> 01:44:01.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the basic question is in terms of public policy, what can be done to empower women?

01:44:01.280 --> 01:44:07.840
[Amit Varma]: But my context for the question is that I often think that there are issues which are social

01:44:07.840 --> 01:44:13.360
[Amit Varma]: problems. And the solutions to them must be social solutions that come from the culture itself.

01:44:13.360 --> 01:44:19.200
[Amit Varma]: And finding either a political solution or a state led solution, or any of those things,

01:44:19.200 --> 01:44:24.720
[Amit Varma]: have their limitations. Is that something you agree with? And in terms of public policy,

01:44:24.720 --> 01:44:30.080
[Amit Varma]: what are the kind of policies you think would help women? And what are the kind of limits you

01:44:30.080 --> 01:44:34.240
[Guest]: think there are to what a government can do? Okay, that's a pretty long question. So let

01:44:34.240 --> 01:44:40.640
[Guest]: me try and remember to answer all aspects of it. You know, this business of mindset change

01:44:40.640 --> 01:44:46.560
[Guest]: is something I've been hearing since December 2012. Back then, the Varma Commission sat down,

01:44:46.560 --> 01:44:52.560
[Guest]: produced a fantastic report. I actually believe in terms of policy, we should just pull out the

01:44:52.560 --> 01:44:59.760
[Guest]: Varma Commission report from whichever dusty shelf it is languishing in. It was really,

01:44:59.760 --> 01:45:06.160
[Guest]: if you remember, it was a manifesto for modern Indian women. Unfortunately, when governments

01:45:06.160 --> 01:45:13.200
[Guest]: rush in to make legislation to appease angry citizens, they brought in features that were

01:45:13.200 --> 01:45:18.640
[Guest]: never recommended. Marital rape was recommended, was ignored, because that will break the structure

01:45:18.640 --> 01:45:23.520
[Guest]: of the Indian family. And as far as I'm concerned, let it break, you know, frankly, because there is

01:45:23.520 --> 01:45:28.960
[Guest]: something broken, there is something fundamentally wrong. We need a new design. So I would say,

01:45:28.960 --> 01:45:34.160
[Guest]: bring back, take a look, somebody needs to take a look at the Varma Commission report once again,

01:45:34.160 --> 01:45:38.880
[Guest]: and say, what did we miss? Because what has happened is that we've lurched from crisis to

01:45:38.880 --> 01:45:44.000
[Guest]: crisis every time responding with a knee-jerk reaction. So when it turns out that one of the

01:45:44.000 --> 01:45:51.360
[Guest]: six men who raped Jyoti Singh Pandey was a minor, we said, okay, we'll solve this problem. Let us

01:45:51.360 --> 01:45:59.200
[Guest]: reduce the age of delinquency from 18 to 16. Now you're having reports of 15-year-old boys,

01:45:59.200 --> 01:46:04.560
[Guest]: 14-year-old boys committing gang rape. What are you going to do? So that's not a solution,

01:46:04.560 --> 01:46:09.680
[Guest]: reducing. Then what did you do? You said, oh, let's raise the age of consent for girls.

01:46:09.680 --> 01:46:15.280
[Guest]: So the age of consent for girls went up from 16 to 18. Now Rukmini Srinivasan of the Hindu,

01:46:15.280 --> 01:46:20.480
[Guest]: at that time she was with the Hindu, did this fascinating study looking at rape trials in

01:46:20.480 --> 01:46:27.280
[Guest]: both Delhi and Bombay. And she found that over 50% of the rape cases that were under trial

01:46:27.280 --> 01:46:34.400
[Guest]: in the various courts in both cities were actually filed by parents because the daughter was, let's

01:46:34.400 --> 01:46:40.960
[Guest]: say, 17 years and nine months. So technically she's a minor. They do not approve of the boyfriend

01:46:40.960 --> 01:46:44.480
[Guest]: because he's from a different caste, he's a different religion, or just because they have

01:46:44.480 --> 01:46:51.040
[Guest]: not selected him. She is in a consensual relationship with him, but he is facing

01:46:51.040 --> 01:46:57.680
[Guest]: rape cases and a rape charge, which will send him to jail for seven years, a minimum of seven years.

01:46:57.680 --> 01:47:05.040
[Guest]: So there is something very broken. Our policies need a relook. And we have a prime minister who

01:47:05.040 --> 01:47:10.160
[Guest]: says he's going to be this revolutionary. We need to go back to the drawing board,

01:47:10.160 --> 01:47:14.640
[Guest]: whether it is talking about family, whether it is talking about workplace design, or whether

01:47:14.640 --> 01:47:20.080
[Guest]: it's just talking about policies and laws on the ground. We need to stop this knee jerk reaction

01:47:20.080 --> 01:47:25.520
[Guest]: and we need to look at it. Actually, I'm very happy that POXO is now looking, I think POXO has

01:47:25.520 --> 01:47:31.120
[Guest]: always been gender blind. We need to make rape gender blind. Why not? Men get raped. You know,

01:47:31.120 --> 01:47:36.160
[Guest]: Derrick O'Brien opened up very recently in parliament and hats off to him for his courage

01:47:36.160 --> 01:47:41.280
[Guest]: in talking about how, but even adult men get raped. Men are raped in prisons.

01:47:42.320 --> 01:47:49.120
[Guest]: We don't want to look at that. So we need really to relook the whole thing. If it means setting up,

01:47:49.120 --> 01:47:52.880
[Guest]: we have the Burma commission, you don't want to look at the Burma commission, set up a new

01:47:52.880 --> 01:47:59.200
[Guest]: commission. You know, the sexual harassment committee was disbanded as it transpires and

01:47:59.200 --> 01:48:05.040
[Guest]: has now been reconstituted with Amit Shah at the head as the home minister.

01:48:05.040 --> 01:48:10.640
[Guest]: I would say he should really constitute a working committee. You have lawyers,

01:48:10.640 --> 01:48:17.840
[Guest]: we have the best legal minds and policy minds in the world. Put them together,

01:48:17.840 --> 01:48:23.360
[Guest]: make them roll up their sleeves and we need a manifesto. We need a new manifesto for women.

01:48:23.360 --> 01:48:29.040
[Guest]: Otherwise, we're going to go on and on and on like a stuck record, moving in circles, moving

01:48:29.040 --> 01:48:33.440
[Guest]: one step forward, two steps backward, two steps forward, one step backward. I mean,

01:48:33.440 --> 01:48:37.440
[Amit Varma]: something's got to give. I mean, what you just said really resonates

01:48:37.440 --> 01:48:43.360
[Amit Varma]: because I think a lot of public policy in India tends to be almost like Jugaar and it's reactive

01:48:43.360 --> 01:48:47.600
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, okay, juvenile has raped. What do we do? Let's bring down the age and

01:48:47.600 --> 01:48:51.600
[Amit Varma]: so on. And you just keep reacting. And a lot of it is also optics. It's for posturing. I mean,

01:48:51.600 --> 01:48:56.160
[Amit Varma]: this whole beti bachao, beti padao, where is it on the ground? Where is the rule of law for women?

01:48:56.160 --> 01:49:00.000
[Guest]: I mean, it's all just talk. Absolutely. In fact, what is worrying is

01:49:00.000 --> 01:49:05.760
[Guest]: Nirmala Sitharaman, the finance minister's statement in the economic survey saying that

01:49:05.760 --> 01:49:10.320
[Guest]: we are now going to expand beti bachao, beti padao, and we're going to call it badlav,

01:49:10.320 --> 01:49:13.280
[Guest]: which stands for beti aapki dhan lakshmi aur rajya lakshmi.

01:49:13.280 --> 01:49:15.680
[Amit Varma]: They're like acronyms. I mean, really? Really?

01:49:17.360 --> 01:49:24.160
[Guest]: Where are we going? You know, we are still a secular country as per our constitution.

01:49:24.160 --> 01:49:30.320
[Guest]: And moreover, besides the nomenclature about dhan lakshmi and rajya lakshmi,

01:49:30.320 --> 01:49:34.800
[Guest]: no, we have a constitution of India. Please hold that up. That is your only holy book.

01:49:35.680 --> 01:49:41.360
[Guest]: You are guaranteeing to women equal status. I don't want my daughter to be dhan lakshmi

01:49:41.360 --> 01:49:46.000
[Guest]: and rajya lakshmi. I want her to be an equal citizen who will be regarded with respect,

01:49:46.000 --> 01:49:49.840
[Amit Varma]: with dignity as any other citizen. I mean, I would argue even with the

01:49:49.840 --> 01:49:54.640
[Amit Varma]: constitution, it doesn't really do enough to protect individual rights. And even a woman,

01:49:54.640 --> 01:49:59.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I had an episode a while back on this with a couple of lawyers where we spoke about

01:49:59.120 --> 01:50:03.760
[Amit Varma]: how so many of the laws in India, like the adultery law, regard women as basically the

01:50:03.760 --> 01:50:09.760
[Amit Varma]: property of men in the way that they are worded. So I think the change that we need is not harkening

01:50:09.760 --> 01:50:14.480
[Amit Varma]: back to this constitution, which especially in recent years has been held up as this mythical

01:50:14.480 --> 01:50:19.840
[Amit Varma]: perfect document, which is not. It's very imperfect and perhaps shall people will make it more

01:50:19.840 --> 01:50:26.400
[Amit Varma]: imperfect, who knows. But to go back to one of those questions in that multi-question series

01:50:26.400 --> 01:50:32.880
[Amit Varma]: that I unfairly thrust at you, to a certain extent, the key here is, you know, the state is always

01:50:32.880 --> 01:50:38.160
[Amit Varma]: going to be reactive and is going to do jogar. To a certain extent, the real change has to kind

01:50:38.160 --> 01:50:43.920
[Amit Varma]: of come from within society and change in our attitudes and whatever, and to some very small

01:50:43.920 --> 01:50:48.560
[Amit Varma]: extent, but important extent, me too, was a part of that, for example, by me just raising awareness

01:50:48.560 --> 01:50:54.960
[Amit Varma]: of these things that we tended to normalize. Through all these years, have you kind of seen

01:50:54.960 --> 01:51:00.720
[Guest]: such change happening? Is there potential? Enormous. Enormous. I see it in my life,

01:51:00.720 --> 01:51:05.520
[Guest]: in the 30 years that I've been working, when I started to now, you know, as I said, sexual

01:51:05.520 --> 01:51:11.280
[Guest]: harassment was not even part of our language. We'd have to use words like he's a creep or he's a

01:51:11.280 --> 01:51:16.720
[Guest]: lech. You know, the word did not exist. The term did not exist. Today, it gives us certain legal

01:51:16.720 --> 01:51:22.080
[Guest]: rights, whether it actually works on the ground or not is another issue, but we have that in law.

01:51:22.080 --> 01:51:26.720
[Guest]: So there's been a sea change. There's been a sea change in attitude in these young girls,

01:51:26.720 --> 01:51:31.440
[Guest]: these 70% teenage girls who are dreaming of careers before marriage. I mean,

01:51:32.080 --> 01:51:37.200
[Guest]: the girls, you're seeing them in sport. In Jharkhand, I just wrote about this football club,

01:51:37.200 --> 01:51:44.400
[Guest]: which is tribal girls, very poor. In fact, Mohs Hima Das, what is, you know, look at her background.

01:51:44.400 --> 01:51:50.000
[Guest]: This is the daughter of a farmer, you know, and you have these great stories coming out of India,

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:55.280
[Guest]: these few girls and each one of them, each one of them, not just improving her own life,

01:51:55.280 --> 01:52:02.480
[Guest]: but acting as a beacon to hundreds, thousands, countless of women who see them. I mean,

01:52:02.480 --> 01:52:07.520
[Guest]: when a young girl sees a Mary Kom, even if it's being played by a Priyanka Chopra,

01:52:07.520 --> 01:52:12.720
[Guest]: she sees her up on the screen. I mean, you know, these are girls who dare to dream.

01:52:13.600 --> 01:52:16.560
[Guest]: I think that is both heartbreaking and also heartening.

01:52:17.120 --> 01:52:22.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and also, you know, like you correctly said, it's not just that Hima Das is a farmer's daughter

01:52:22.000 --> 01:52:26.000
[Amit Varma]: come good, and that's a great story in itself. But you think of the million farmer's daughters

01:52:26.000 --> 01:52:30.320
[Amit Varma]: who watch her and who say that I don't just have to be a farmer's daughter or a farmer's wife.

01:52:30.320 --> 01:52:35.360
[Amit Varma]: This is probably something else. So I'll kind of end on a question about,

01:52:36.560 --> 01:52:43.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, having sort of followed women in India, what's been happening socially and

01:52:43.040 --> 01:52:47.760
[Amit Varma]: politically and culturally over the last 30 years, looking into the future, let's just say looking

01:52:47.760 --> 01:52:52.800
[Amit Varma]: into the next 10 years and not going beyond that, what gives you hope and what gives you despair

01:52:52.800 --> 01:52:59.680
[Guest]: about the state of women in India? Well, the statistics are grim. So really, that is

01:52:59.680 --> 01:53:05.280
[Guest]: cause for despair and worry. Because whichever even there is evidence that the Beti Bachao has

01:53:05.280 --> 01:53:12.960
[Guest]: not worked uniformly, sex ratio is going on declining. And the fact that there is no one

01:53:12.960 --> 01:53:19.040
[Guest]: who really is talking about it, the silent war against half your country's population,

01:53:19.040 --> 01:53:26.400
[Guest]: or less than half, because we've killed off so many, is cause for despair, concern, worry.

01:53:27.440 --> 01:53:33.520
[Guest]: You know, as a citizen, as a woman, as a mother of daughters, I worry about what will happen,

01:53:34.240 --> 01:53:38.320
[Guest]: you know, down the road, what is going to happen tomorrow, forget about 10 years.

01:53:38.320 --> 01:53:45.840
[Guest]: The data is very, very grim. And I feel that we as a society, we're not thinking about this.

01:53:45.840 --> 01:53:50.480
[Guest]: You know, when you talk of mindset change, mindset change is not something so difficult.

01:53:50.480 --> 01:53:55.200
[Guest]: You're talking about a new education policy, for instance, am I seeing anything on mindset

01:53:55.200 --> 01:53:59.440
[Guest]: change over there? I mean, are we just going to tinker with history books and change names from

01:53:59.440 --> 01:54:05.200
[Guest]: Delhi to Delhi and say Mughals were very bad people? And, you know, Akbar was a villain,

01:54:05.200 --> 01:54:10.400
[Guest]: but Rana Pratap, you know, let's get out of these debates. What is sex education? You know,

01:54:10.400 --> 01:54:16.240
[Guest]: it's such a red letter, by God, no, no, no, as a society, what is sex education? It's teaching

01:54:16.240 --> 01:54:21.600
[Guest]: boys and girls to respect each other. Instead, you have textbooks, ma gol gol roti banati hai.

01:54:21.600 --> 01:54:28.640
[Guest]: So how does mindset change happen? But all you have to do is tell boys, you know, ask.

01:54:29.520 --> 01:54:34.240
[Guest]: We're not saying that don't have sex, we're saying just ask. You know, it's not such a

01:54:34.240 --> 01:54:40.960
[Guest]: revolutionary concept. Understand, empathize. That's missing in our, why are we not talking

01:54:40.960 --> 01:54:46.080
[Guest]: about it in this new education curriculum? Why is it not anybody's problem? We are

01:54:46.880 --> 01:54:52.080
[Guest]: half this nation's population. Why is it not anyone's problem? Not policymakers,

01:54:52.080 --> 01:54:57.360
[Guest]: not governments, even the judiciary. Even though I say that often the judiciary is the last hope

01:54:57.360 --> 01:55:03.040
[Guest]: for women and there's certainly, you know, adultery that you talked about is gone. 377 is gone.

01:55:03.040 --> 01:55:09.360
[Guest]: Triple talaq was, let's not forget, it was banned by the Supreme Court, not by the government. So

01:55:09.360 --> 01:55:13.680
[Guest]: the Supreme Court in many ways is progressive. And then you will have some ridiculous judgment

01:55:13.680 --> 01:55:18.640
[Guest]: coming where court is referring to a live-in partner as a keep. What the hell is a keep,

01:55:18.640 --> 01:55:24.880
[Guest]: yeah? Who uses these words? You know, so it's like, you just need something radical. And if

01:55:24.880 --> 01:55:30.000
[Guest]: you don't do it, and this is what gives me hope, I think you have a generation of girls who will

01:55:30.000 --> 01:55:36.640
[Guest]: take it. It doesn't matter if you don't give it to us, we will take it. On that emphatic hopeful

